<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Extreme Right Party Proposes Constitutional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- France's extreme right party, the
National Front (FN), today called for a constitutional reform to
adding what it called "the principle of national preference"
into the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Holding in Strasbourg its 10th national congress session which
was strongly protested over the past two days, the FN also
presented a dozen other "projects of law" to show its
determination to share government power in the future, reported
the Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Among the proposals are a call for the revival of the death
penalty, the establishment of a "parent's income" for families
with at least one French parent, tightening of conditions for
naturalization of foreigners, and limiting the right of foreigners
to reside in France.
</P>
<P>
The FN also proposed to impose taxes on companies employing
foreign workers, and to scrap the principle of free trade by
installing "customs sampling for French employment" restricting
imports of foreign goods.
</P>
<P>
The party of Jean-Marie Le Pen also proposed the clause on
"referendum of popular initiative at national and local level"
in the constitution.
</P>
<P>
It called for the abolition of the 1972 Pleven law on cracking
down on offenses in provocating racial and religious
discrimination, hatred, and violence.
</P>
<P>
Since several trade unions controlled by the FN were outlawed
in the past, the FN called for "establishment and guarantee of
real union liberty."
</P>
<P>
It called for abolishing the system of what it called
"presumption of representativity" in unions, and suggested a 5
percent votes in professional elections as the starting line
for being represented in unions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
