<HEADLINE> Cameroun: Curfew Delared in North West Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yaounde, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A dust-to-dawn curfew was declared on
Sturday throughout North West Province in Cameroun by the governor
of the province to ensure public orders, according to a statement
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Governor Fai Yengo Francis said that the
movements of people in the province are strictly forbiden from
7 pm to 6 am everyday since Saturday. All meetings and
gatherings are also prohibited.
</P>
<P>
The curfew will be lifted as soon as total calm returns to the
province, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the use of fire arms and guns at funerals
and other ceremonies are banned during the set hours.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, armed individuals attacked civilian and security
installations in Bui, Mezam and Momo divisions of the province.
Three army officers were killed and several civillians wounded
the local press reported here today.
</P>
<P>
A group of gunmen killed a gendarmerie officer on guard in the
gendarmerie brigade in Jakiri of Bui Division on Thurday night.
At the same time, Kumbo of Bui was attacked. The house of the
divisional officer for Kumbo was burned down. In Oku of
Bui, the divisional officer as well as some gendarmerie officers
were taken hostage and held for about 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The next day, the armed individuals attacked Bamenda of Mezam,
the capital of the province, as well as Mbengwi of Momo and
killed another two gendarmerie officers.
</P>
<P>
So far, 12 people have been arrested at Mbengwi. Some of them are
connected with the stealing of the explosives on March 23 from a road
construction company, Razel, in Bamenda. Investigation is
now being carried out. enditem

