<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chip Makers Fall into Tense Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Advanced Micro Devices (AMD)
Company will launch its K6 chip, which comes closer than ever to
matching or beating the performance of Intel chips, according to a
report of the USA Today Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new computer chip is expected to enhance the competition of
the Central Processing Unit (CPU) market, about 85 percent of
which is dominated by Intel.
</P>
<P>
AMD has not released pricing yet, the paper said. But analysts
expect the K6 to be 20 percent to 25 percent cheaper than
comparable Intel chips. That should make it attractive to
personal-computer makers, who have almost no alternative other
than Intel.
</P>
<P>
The "Intel Inside" label on PCs has brought great benefits to
the Intel Corp. Consumers often refer to PCs as "Intel" PCs --
instead of naming the actual PC-maker.
</P>
<P>
The California-based AMD has been struggling. It and
Texas-based Cyrix split the 15 percent that Intel doesn't own. The
K6 is AMD's equivalent of Intel's Pentium II, which will be
introduced next month. According to the magazine of PC World, a
233-megahertz K6 comes close to matching the performance of a
266-MHz Intel Pentium II.
</P>
<P>
With performance that close, the K6's lower price could make it
attractive. As another cost-saver, the K6 fits into existing PC
motherboards, the board that holds a PC's chips. Pentium II will
need new motherboard designs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
