<HEADLINE> Black Rhino Population Increasing in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The population of Zimbabwe's black
rhino which had been reduced drastically due to poaching activities
is now increasing by more than 10 percent annually due to an
improved habitat and stepping up of security activities, local
press reported said today.
</P>
<P>
Norman English, a warden for Sinamatella Intensive Protection Zone
Camp in the Hwange National Park in western Zimbabwe where most of the
black rhino in Zimbabwe is located, said high security activities had
resulted in zero anti-poaching activities in the area for the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
However, he could not disclose the current number of black rhino in
the area for security reason, although the whole country was
estimated to have about 300 of the animals, which used to number
more than 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
''The national parks department and its associates are effectively
monioring poaching activities using helicopters and foot patrols,''
he said. enditem

