<HEADLINE> S.Africa Prepares for Peace Talks on Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 31 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is making
preparations for proposed peace talks between the Zairean government
and rebels, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Arrangements for the peace talks are going ahead but there is
still no confirmation about where and when the talks will be
held, said the source.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the Department of Foreign Affairs Pieter
Swanepoel said in Cape Town today that officials from his
department had been in contact with the two warring parties, and
received the go-ahead to make preparations for the talks.
</P>
<P>
However, Swanepoel did not elaborate on what would be
discussed at the talks.
</P>
<P>
"We are providing a venue. Further than that we cannot
comment," he said.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day state visit to India last week, President
Nelson Mandela announced that South Africa is to host the Zaire
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
A rebel spokesman, Kongolo Mwenze, said in Goma, eastern Zaire
on Sunday that they were willing to hold preliminary peace talks
as early as Thursday in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mwenze said the proposed talks, if taking place this week,
would focus on setting up a meeting between President Mobutu
Sese Seko and rebel leader Laurent-Desire Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The Zairean government did not make any comment on the rebel
remarks. enditem

