<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Vow to Make Good on Freezing Ties With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League's resolution to
halt steps to normalize ties with Israel, which sends a clear
signal to the U.S. and Israel that peace cannot be played with,
will be implemented immediately, Arab ministers said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Syria-sponsored resolution, approved at a closed-door
session Sunday night, recommended Arab states reactivate the
economic boycott of Israel, stop normalization steps, close
Israeli offices and missions and pull out of multilateral talks
on aspects of Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
It will be included in a joint communique at the end of the
two-day meeting as a joint Arab response to Israel's Judaization
attempt on Jerusalem through building Jewish settlement on the
Arab sector of the city.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz said the decision "sent
a clear signal to Israel to deal with peace genuinely."
</P>
<P>
"It is also a message to the U.S. to return to the principles
of the peace process as an honest broker," he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters on the second day of the Arab League's
107th ministerial session, Boueiz said the decision will be set in
motion immediately, and the activities of the six Arab missions
and agencies in Israel will be halted.
</P>
<P>
Israel has diplomatic ties with Egypt and Jordan and set up
trade links with Morocco, Tunisia, Qatar and Oman.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to implement the decision at this particular
grave phase," he said, terming the recent Israeli practices as a
devastation to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The resolution recommended Arab countries to resume the
economic embargo imposed on Israel since 1948 and partially eased
after the 1993 Palestinian-Israeli peace accords. Multilateral
peace talks on water, economic cooperation, Palestinian refugees,
the environment and disarmament would be shelved, too.
</P>
<P>
Syria supports the idea and said the resolution does not require
the consent of Arab leaders because it fits in the scope of the
recent Arab summit resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the sidelines of the meeting today, Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouq al-Shara said that Arab leaders at the summit
last June linked normalization with Israel to progress on the
peace track.
</P>
<P>
"Arab foreign ministers are following the instructions of
their leaders, namely that multilateral negotiations be
suspended until Israel halts its destructive practices against
peace," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Vow to Make Good on Freezing Ties With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Faisal Husseini, the Palestinian
official in charge of Jerusalem affairs, today lauded the Arab
League's decision to freeze normalization with Israel, which came
after a fiery appeal by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
He termed the two-day discussions at the meetings as very
serious in a pre-departure statement after attending the foreign
ministerial session.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to halt multilateral talks and normalization
with Israel could affect the latter's peace policy," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also dismissed Israeli charges that the Palestinian
National Authority had given the green light to violence in
Israel and pinned the blame on Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has damaged the credibility of the peace process and
offered the proper climate to those who wanted to act separately
against peace on grounds that the process had become obsolete, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian official also regretted the U.S. use of its
veto power twice in a month in favor of Israel's settlement
policy.
</P>
<P>
"Regrettably, America has contributed to the damaging of the
credibility of the peace process and is thus poisoning the
climate in the Middle East," he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Israel's biggest Arab partner, today criticized
Israel's reaction to the Arab resolution as a mere "diatribe"
that is part of "violent verbal attacks."
</P>
<P>
Israel has shrugged off Arab League decision, saying that
Israel will not be deterred by the "threats made in Cairo and
Rabat," where a similar resolution was adopted at the Islamic
countries' Jerusalem Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, speaking to reporters at
the League headquarters, urged Israel to see that the Arabs
really meant it when they made the decision. "It is better for
Israel to realize the actual situation," he added.
</P>
<P>
Moussa expressed the hope that such a stance could make
Washington change its position in the interest of peace.
</P>
<P>
"Now Washington knows our viewpoint and the peace process has
to go forward because the situation is very bad," he added.
</P>
<P>
Omani Foreign Minister Yusef Ben-Alawi told the press that
the Arabs were "serious" about halting normalization with Israel
if it did not change its policy toward peace.
</P>
<P>
It is up to Israel, he said, to chose normalization with the
Arabs or continue its "inflexible policies."
</P>
<P>
Israel's ground-breaking for a 6,500-unit Jewish neighborhood
in East Jerusalem has stalled peace talks and sparked 12 days of
Palestinian riots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
