<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6th Conference of African Ministers of Finance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The sixth session of the
Conference of African Ministers of Finance opened today at the
U.N. Conference Center here.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address, Ethiopian Deputy Prime Minister Kassu
Ilala said Sub-Saharan Africa's gross domestic product (GDP) rose
by four percent in 1995, compared to the averaging 1.4 percent
increase in the period 1991-1995.
</P>
<P>
"This was the first time in more than a decade that Africa
registered a positive growth in its per capita income. Forecasts
for 1996 point to an even more buoyant outcome," Kassu said.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that the "encouraging trend is a result of
the serious choices and sometimes the painful economic measures
taken by" African countries.
</P>
<P>
Kassu said Sub-Saharan Africa's debt to export ratio reached
270 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The debt situation seriously impedes Africa's chances for
sustainable growth and development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In some extreme cases, debt servicing is taking up to 90
percent of budgetary resources and in spite of all efforts to
repay what we can, arrears continue to accumulate," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped the conference will focus on the critical
thematic issues -- financial reforms, debt management and
exchange rate mechanisms -- that will support Africa's effort to
maintain this momentum and meet the challenges of sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
K.Y. Amoako, the U.N. Under Secretary General and Executive
Secretary of the Economic Commission for Africa, said "In
Sub-Saharan Africa official development assistance accounts for a
higher proportion of external financial flows than to any other
developing region."
</P>
<P>
Amoako noted that while official development assistance is
declining worldwide, record levels of private capital are flowing
to developing countries, adding private capital flows to the
developing world soared from 44 billion U.S. Dollars in 1990 to
244 billion Dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that "the flows to Africa are lower,
as a percentage of GDP than all other developing regions. Only
about three percent of all the flows of private capital go to
sub-Saharan Africa."
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Organization of African Unity Salim
Ahmed Salim told participants: "The sound management of money
and finance is key to the success of any economic endeavor".
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, for reasons both internal and external, most
of our countries have not been able to ensure a sound management
of this important sector," he said.
</P>
<P>
Salim stressed that "as we are engaged in reforming our
economies to meet the challenges of globalization and
competitiveness, it is imperative to reform our financial systems
taking into account the new realities of international economic
relations''.
</P>
<P>
Referring to African debt crisis, he said that "the stock of
Africa's debt is today estimated at more than 340 billion
Dollars, while the debt servicing payments amount to 24 billion
Dollars."
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting will discuss growth and development
finance in Africa at the turn of the century and the role for
the multilateral financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Among topics are financial sector reforms in Africa,
challenges of the African debt problem and emerging capital
markets in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will adopt resolutions and declaration proposed by
experts meeting which was held here last week. enditem

=03311737

=03311744
