<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denounces Arab Decision to Freeze Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu today strongly denounced the decision by Arab
countries to freeze ties with Israel, forecasting that it would
not work.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was reacting to the resolution adopted by the
meeting of Foreign Ministers of the Arab League in Cairo, which
called for freezing ties with Israel to protest its policies of
building settlements in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
He denounced the resolution as "absurd," saying Israel as a
strong and modern economy would not be cowed by such coercion.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think these sort of attempts to reconstitute boycott
can go anywhere. It did not go anywhere when Israel was a
fledgling country with small economy, and today we are a very
strong country with very strong economy with international
technological power. It did not work then, it won't work now,"
he told the Knesset (Parliament) Foreign Affairs and Defense
Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said that the only way to resolve the differences between
Israel and Arab countries was to negotiate. "We cannot accept
the concept of peace in which we are coerced by political
warfare or by threats of terror and threats of violence," he
added.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the state-run Israel Radio, Netanyahu
reiterated his tough stance on the issue of building settlements
in East Jerusalem or elsewhere on the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel would not halt the controversial
construction in Har Homa of East Jerusalem, because he would
never allow Jerusalem to be redivided like the German city of
Berlin during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu expressed deep disappointment with Egypt, the first
Arab country to make peace with Israel, for initiating the Arab
boycott. "I think the Egyptians have to make up their mind about
a Middle East of peace or a Middle East of perpetual conflicts,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Arab boycott came against the backdrop that the
Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations were stalled because of
Israel's decision to build the Har Homa settlement. The deadlock
has led to a rising tension between the two sides as
stone-throwing Palestinian protesters have been clashing with
Israeli soldiers across the territories for the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Following the suicide bombing in Tel Aviv on March 21, which
killed four people and wounded dozens of others, Israel has
toughened its position against the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) by conditioning the resumption of peace talks on the PNA's
promise to launch long-term crackdown on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli opposition parties today blasted Netanyahu's
hardline policies for leading to Israel's isolation and
deterioration in ties with the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Ehud Barak, heir-apparent of the Labor Party, said he was
deeply disturbed by the current situation. He criticized
Netanyahu for having destroyed the mutual Israeli-Arab confidence
which was painstakingly built by the previous Labor
government. He urged Netanyahu to "stop the escalation and find a
way to restore contacts with Arab leaders."
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid also expressed concern about what
he described as "total collapse" of Israeli-Arab peace process
in the region. He blamed the Netanyahu government for creating
the current "miserable and bad situation". 
</P>
</TEXT>
