<HEADLINE> Landslide Destroys Village in Northwest Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A landslide has destroyed 70
percent of a village in Iran's northwestern province of East
Azarbaijan province, Iran's official news agency IRNA reported
today.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said 30 of 65 families living in the Nasir-Abad village,
about 700 kilometers northwest of Tehran, have been forced to
evacuate their homes and live in Tabriz temporarily.
</P>
<P>
There are no reports of casualties.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the remaining 35 families have taken
shelter in the neighboring Mehtarlu village.
</P>
<P>
However, the report did not mention when the landslide
happened.
</P>
<P>
Landslide has intensified in the region since a deadly
earthquake shook the nearby Ardebil province on February 28, which
killed about 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the Nasir-Abad village cannot be
reconstructed and its inhabitants should be transferred to safe
area.
</P>
<P>
The affected families will receive free plots of land and soft
loans worth 2,200 U.S. dollars to build their new homes in other
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
