<HEADLINE> Kuwait Likely to Postpone British Missile Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait may postpone a
British missile deal as the parliament today advised the
government to do so.
</P>
<P>
Adnan Abdel Samad, spokesman of the Committee for the
Protection of Public Funds of the National Assembly, said today
that the deal was on the parliament agenda to reconsider the
report of the Defense Ministry's technical committee regarding the
deal.
</P>
<P>
Several parliamentary members opposed to the deal have asked
the government to launch investigation into the deal.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is preparing to buy some surface-to-surface missiles to
be mounted on its French-made patrol boats. Both France and
Britain were competing to gain the deal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The deal was estimated at about 100 million U.S. dollars. It
sparked a dispute between the government and the National
Assembly after reports claimed that the British offer was favored
to a better French deal.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti previous parliament which ended its term in October,
1996 was told that the French offer was cheaper and better and the
French missiles fit better on the French-made gunboats. It asked
Kuwaiti Defense Ministry to form a new committee to study the two
offers and select the best.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Defense Ministry initialed the contract with the
British government, maintaining that the British Seaskua missile
were better than the French MM15.
</P>
<P>
Some cabinet ministers said the deal has not been finalized
yet. 
</P>
