<HEADLINE> UN Creates 5,000 Jobs in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has created
more than 5,000 jobs for former faction fighters and civilians in
Liberia to help rebuild the war-ravaged country, a report reaching
here said today.
</P>
<P>
Under the UN's Civil Reconstruction Team's program launched last
December to help reinsert former fighters into civil society,
ex-guerillas and community workers are carrying out work such as
cleaning drainage systems and repairing roads, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Each team member receives one U.S. dollar and a free lunch per day.
</P>
<P>
"While working to improve the situation in their communities, the
work buys them time for exploring other ways of getting on with their
lives," said Johan Heffinck, project manager of the UN office
implementing the program.
</P>
<P>
The Resident Representative of the United Nations Development
Program in Liberia, Adama Guido said, "Getting former combatants off
the streets and back into civil society is essential for Liberia's
transition towards peace and democracy."
</P>
<P>
Guido said that since the first team was set up in December last
year, an average of 300 jobs have been created on a weekly basis, and
there are now a total of 43 teams working in Lofa, Bong, Grqnd Bassa,
Margibi, Montserado and Bomi counties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
