<HEADLINE> Lebanese Minister: Contacts for Arab Summit Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Arab countries are contacting with
each other for a summit, Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz
announced here this evening.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz, who returned home today after attending the two-day
107th conference of the Arab League Council held in the Egyptian
capital of Cairo Sunday and Monday, also stressed the necessity to
"unify the Arab rank" within this framework.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the Beirut International Airport, he
confirmed that there are also contacts in the entire Arab world to
press for a role of the United States as a "just intermediary and
pushing power" in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
A just role of the U.S. "constitutes a basic pillar of the
peace process and the peace process can not continue without
this role," the Lebanese foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
"There are contacts and messages asking the U.S. to return to
this role if it really wants the peace process to be saved from
the present crisis," Boueiz added.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on a recent tour of U.S. Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross in Rabat, Morocco and Israel, Boueiz said, "if
there is any new U.S. move, we hope that his move will be serious
and will be that of an impartial mediator and a pushing power."
</P>
<P>
"We are still seeking a real peace, and we are still asking the
U.S. to fully play its role," the foreign minister reiterated.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the decisions adopted by the Arab League
Council conference, the foreign minister said that the message
from these decisions was "very clear."
</P>
<P>
In its final declaration, the council called on all the Arab
states to freeze the normalization of ties with Israel and to
close their representative offices in the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to make the Israelis to understand and to know
that it impossibly obtains all the peace benefits meanwhile
abrogates the benefits of others," Boueiz underlined.
</P>
<P>
The first thing the Arabs should do from now on is to "reunify
their positions and to re-establish the Arab solidarity out of the
belief that the peace is either to be comprehensive or not to be,"
he added. 
