<HEADLINE> Liberia's Taylor Against Change in Election Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A Liberian presidential candidate and
former warlord, Charles Taylor, has joined in the chorus of the
international community for efforts to hold the country's elections on
May 30 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Anything that would warrant changing the election date, which would
lead to so many complexities, must be avoided, said Taylor, who many
observers believe is one of the strongmen in the race for presidency.
</P>
<P>
"If the election date is shifted forward, it means I will have to
return to the Council (of State) and start all over again, in spite of
the fact that I have met my own part of the agreement," he said,
quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, along with two other major former warlords Alhaji Kromah
and George Boley, resigned the post of vice-chairman of the ruling
Council of State a month ago to contest for the presidency in
elections.
</P>
<P>
With only two months to go, the slow pace of preparations for the
May 30 polls, particularly the delay in the induction of Liberia's
election commission and supreme court, has aroused concern from the
international community over whether the election can be held as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Both United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan and Nigerian Head
of State General Sani Abacha, who is also chairman of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS), have called on the Liberian
Council of State for efforts to avoid a postponement of the elections.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with visiting Nigerian journalists in Monrovia, the
Liberian capital, over the weekend, Taylor disclosed that he had
called for an emergency meeting of the council to settle the dispute
over the chairmanship of the electoral commission.
</P>
<P>
It must be settled by April 1 and the body inaugurated by April 2
as recommended by ECOWAS, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
As for the claims that the election period was too short, Taylor
said "Liberia's situation is not a normal one and no sound mind should
expect the normal thing to happen. Everyone is now interested in
re-building the society and putting the past behind."
</P>
<P>
According to the revised Abuja peace accord, signed last August to
end the seven-year-old civil war in Liberia, general and presidential
elections should be held on May 30 and a new democratic government
installed on June 15.
</P>
<P>
Taylor also pledged to support the ECOWAS peace-keeping plan if he
became the president of Liberia, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Post-election Liberia should be one of healing old wounds and
re-integration of everyone in the society, he said, adding that
re-distribution of wealth was no necessary in the country.
</P>
<P>
The concentration of wealth in the hands of just about 0.2 percent
of the population was the cause of the crisis in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, presidential candidate of the National Patriotic Party,
said the alliance of seven other parties in the election was not a
threat to him.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
