<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-31 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Adopt Resolutions on Jerusalem and Other </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League Council ended its
107th meeting here this evening after adopting several
resolutions on Jerusalem, Libya, Somalia and other hot spots
while postponing four other resolutions for further examination.
</P>
<P>
The delayed resolutions are related to the statute of the Arab
Court of Justice, the code of honor for Arab security and
cooperation, the mechanism for administering and settling Arab
disputes and Arab Union project.
</P>
<P>
In a final joint communique issued at the end of the two-day
ministerial meeting, the Arab League urged countries building
ties with Israel to reconsider the normalization steps and resume
the economic embargo imposed on Israel since 1948 and partially
eased after the 1993 Palestinian-Israeli peace accords.
</P>
<P>
While trade links with Tunisia, Morocco, Qatar and Oman might
be cut, Israel's peace treaties with Egypt and Jordan and a
string of agreements with the Palestinians would not be affected.
</P>
<P>
It also urged a suspension of multilateral peace talks on
water, economic cooperation, Palestinian refugees, the
environment and disarmament, in protest against Israel's breaking
ground for a 6,500-unit Jewish neighborhood in Arab East
Jerusalem, captured in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, approved during a closed-door session Sunday
night, shaped up the common Arab stance in response to Israel's
controversial Jewish housing project that has stalled the peace
process and sparked 12 days of Palestinian rioting.
</P>
<P>
The Syria-sponsored resolution denounced the Israeli
Judaization attempt on Jerusalem before promised talks on final
status of the occupied Palestinian lands. Palestinians want the
Arab sector of the city as a future capital while Israel wants it
undivided under Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
It also called upon Russia and the U.S., the two co-sponsors
of the Mideast peace process to push Israel to "abide by U.N.
Security Council resolutions 252 and 476 that consider Israeli
measures in Jerusalem as null and void."
</P>
<P>
Arab ministers have made clear that they will set the
resolution in motion immediately and thus send a clear signal to
Israel and the U.S. that peace can not be tampered with.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Husseini, the Palestinian official in charge of the
Jerusalem affairs, expressed the hope that the decision to halt
multilateral talks and normalization with Israel "could sway the
latter's peace policy."
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa urged Israel to realize
that Arabs really mean it when they made the decision and
overhaul its settlement decision.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Lebanon both expected the resolution would help
"return the U.S. back to the principles of the peace process as
an honest broker."
</P>
<P>
Despite the Arab appeal, Israel has shrugged off the decision,
saying that it will not be deterred by "the threats made in Cairo
and Rabat," where a similar resolution was adopted at the Islamic
countries' Jerusalem Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
While shedding limelight on Jerusalem, the Arab League Council
also gives recommendations on the Somali conflicts, calling upon
all factions to immediately stop fighting and settle their
differences by means of dialogue and within the framework of
national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
In another move, the Council reiterated its solidarity with
Libya and called for the U.N. Security Council to hold
a special session to decide on a peaceful end to the crisis
facing the country.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed overall sanctions on Libya in April
1992 after Libya refused to surrender suspects in the 1988
bombing of Pan America Flight 103 jet over Lockbie, Scotland,
killing 270 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Accused of Trying to Sell Mozambique's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Head of the Mozambican National
Tourism Department (DNT) Arlindo Langa here today accused a South
African, Richard Makin, of attempting to sell Mozambique's
Paraiso Island.
</P>
<P>
Makin has advertised the island, located in Vilanculos
County, Inhambane Province in southern Mozambique, for sale at
the price of 3.5 million U.S. Dollars through South African and
international media, Langa said.
</P>
<P>
Makin in 1995 got the licenses from the Mozambican government
to run two dilapidated hotels named Dona Ana and Santa Carolina
on the island on condition that he should renovate them first,
Langa said.
</P>
<P>
However, it was said that Makin received foreign tourists in
the two hotels with no repairs made and the Mozambican side
blamed him for staining the country's image.
</P>
<P>
Then, the Mozambican government revoked Makin's licenses and
fined him 10 million Meticais (870 Dollars).
</P>
<P>
In response, Makin lodged legal suits in both Mozambique and
South Africa against his partners -- the DNT and the Mozambican
Popular Development Bank (BPD).
</P>
<P>
Under a court decision in South Africa last year, the banking
accounts of the DNT and BPD in South Africa, worth about two
million Dollars, were frozen.
</P>
<P>
Makin is not the owner of the island or the hotels and he has
no rights to sell the island which belongs to Mozambique, said
Langa.
</P>
<P>
Makin's move is aimed to hinder the development of
Mozambique's tourism, Langa charged. enditem

