<HEADLINE> Students Arrested in Anti-Israeli Protests in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The Attorney General of the
Egyptian State Security Prosecution today ordered the detention of
five Cairo University students for breaching public order during
the anti-Israeli demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
The students, jailed for 15 days pending investigations, were
accused of distributing leaflets instigating violence and
breaching the peace during the anti-Israeli protest.
</P>
<P>
They were seized last week during or after a string of campus
protests against Israel's plans to build a Jewish housing project
in Arab East Jerusalem, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day demonstrations on campus early last week,
Cairo University students denounced the Abu Ghneim or Har Homa
project and Israeli attempts to Judaize Jerusalem, which is holy
to Christians, Muslims and Jews alike.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators held banners and shouted slogans such as
"Jerusalem is Arab," and burned the national flag of Israel. They
also called for expelling the Israeli ambassador here and
withdrawing the Egyptian ambassador from Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
During the past week, thousands of Alexandria University
students, members of trade unions and opposition parties as well
as woman activists have staged separate demonstrations in protest
of the Israeli settlement policy.
</P>
<P>
Arabs are infuriated by the Israeli housing project for Jews,
which they said caused a breakdown of Palestinian-Israeli
relations.
</P>
