<HEADLINE> Oklahoma City Bombing Trial Begins With Jury Selection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The trial in the 1995 Oklahoma
City bombing got under way today in the U.S. District Court in
Denver, with judge Richard Matsch delivering a brief explanation
of the jury selection process.
</P>
<P>
In the packed courtroom were defendant Timothy McVeigh, his
legal team led by Oklahoma lawyer Stephen Jones, and U.S. Attorney
Joseph Hartzler's prosecution unit, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
Matsch interviewed the first of 352 prospective jurors, from
which a jury of 12 and six alternates will be chosen to hear
months of testimony.
</P>
<P>
McVeigh is charged with the worst case of domestic terrorism in
U.S. history -- the bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal
Building on April 19, 1995, that killed 168 and injured 500.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of journalists are in Denver for the start of the
trial but the number is expected to dwindle as Matsch and lawyers
on both sides go through the jury selection process.
</P>
<P>
If McVeigh is convicted, whether he is sentenced to death will
be up to the jury. Under federal law, anyone opposed to the death
penalty in all circumstances cannot serve as a juror in a capital
case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
