<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Trade Deficit Hits 7.43 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's trade deficit reached
7.43 billion U.S. dollars in the first three months, up 78.3
percent over a year ago, the Industry and Energy Ministry reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Exports totaled 29.809 billion dollars and imports 37.239
billion dollars respectively, according to the ministry's trade
estimates.
</P>
<P>
However, the deficit was better than the projected 7.7 billion
dollars, thanks to a slight recovery in the semiconductor sector
and the increasing exports of other items.
</P>
<P>
Deficit in the first three months were 3.466 billion dollars,
2.088 billion dollars and 1.876 billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter's trade deficit surpassed half of the
government's 14-billion-dollar projection for the whole year,
raising fears that it would be an even worse year than the
previous one when the nation suffered its worst-ever trade loss of
more than 15 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the Ministry forecast that the trade deficit will
gradually improve, as the export is decreasing at a more slow
pace, from 8.7 percent in January to 4.8 percent in February and
2.9 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
While exports to the developed nations declined 15.3 percent to
10.504 billion dollars, those to the developing countries
increased 3.3 percent to 13.767 billion dollars, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
