<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rumors on Traveling to Hong Kong Refuted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Rumors are groundless that the
policies concerning inland personnel traveling to and from Hong
Kong will be changed before and after its return to the
motherland, it was announced today.
</P>
<P>
The Public Security Department of south China's Guangdong
Province held a news conference today to deny the recent
widespread rumors, and to publicize the state's policies and
regulations on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) clearly defines that strict control will continue to be
imposed on inland personnel going to Hong Kong after the return,
and that five current practices will continue as they are:
</P>
<P>
-- The existing regulations and practices concerning inland
personnel and Hong Kong people going and coming remain basically
unchanged;
</P>
<P>
-- The regulation remains as it is now that inland qualified
applicants cannot go to Hong Kong before receiving approval;
</P>
<P>
-- Border checks remain unchanged by the HKSAR and inland
authorities;
</P>
<P>
-- The principle to limit approvals remains as is;
</P>
<P>
-- The principle remains unchanged to repatriate all those who
illegally enter and stay in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
