<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Introduce Accidental Injury Insurance For Coal Miners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China's six million coal miners
will have better protected rights and interests after July 1, when
China requires mining managements to buy accidental injury
insurance.
</P>
<P>
China is putting the final touches on a set of regulations to
introduce this type of insurance coverage in the coal industry,
said Wang Xiaoqi, general director of the Social Insurance
Management Bureau of the Ministry of Coal Industry.
</P>
<P>
He said that the regulations are made in accordance with the
coal mining law issued last year, and that the new rules make it
mandatory for all coal mining companies to provide the coverage
for their workers.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the coal mining industry sees the
highest death tolls and numbers of injuries among all industrial
sectors in the country, but the workers are receiving very low
financial compensation.
</P>
<P>
"The financial compensation for killed or injured coal miners
is largely paid in accordance with the regulations set in 1953,"
he said, adding that the new regulations will enable relatives of
a worker killed in a mining accident to receive around 50,000
yuan, more than 20 times the amount of compensation they receive
now.
</P>
<P>
He said that the coal industry has set different insurance
costs for coal mining companies in keeping with their
profitability and the levels of their workers' salaries.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the insurance fee set by the ministry is still
inadequate, because the entire coal industry is still losing money.
</P>
<P>
China's major state-owned coal mines employ 3.26 million
workers -- about half of the country's total coal mining workforce
-- and also provide welfare for 1.17 million retired workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Raises Electricity, Heating Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria today increased electricity
and heating prices by 30 percent and 70 percent respectively,
local press reported.
</P>
<P>
It is the third time this year that the government has lifted
fuel prices drastically.
</P>
<P>
The government said the price hikes were part of a price reform
rather than a decision under the pressure of inflation. The aim is
to make power prices closer to the standard set by the World Bank
for receiving its loans.
</P>
<P>
Official forecasts show that the price of bread, Bulgarians'
staple food, will rise by 10.2 percent due to the power price
hikes.
</P>
<P>
Currency devaluation and inflation has prompted the government
to raise the prices for power, coal, gas and oil by 45 percent and
48 percent respectively in January and February. But the
government said inflation has been brought under control last
month.
</P>
<P>
Subsidies will be given to poor families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
