<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Police Earn Big Bonanza by Hiring out Officers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong police made 12 million
HK dollars (1.54 million US dollars) in the past financial year by
hiring out officers, today's Hong Kong Standard reported.
</P>
<P>
The earnings, up 16 percent over the previous financial year,
are credited to the Police Welfare Fund.
</P>
<P>
The hourly rate is 125 HK dollars (16 US dollars) for a
constable, 189 HK dollars for a sergeant (24 US dollars), 398 HK
dollars (51 US dollars) for an inspectorate officer and 731 HK
dollars (94 US dollars) for a superintendent with a minimum charge
of four hours, the English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
One of the leading clients is the Hong Kong Jockey Club which
has to pay for the deployment of police officers at race courses
for every meeting.
</P>
<P>
A club spokesman said: "We need the deployment of police
officers for crowd control and cash custody. Their presence is
good for us and the race-goers."
</P>
<P>
And the Hong Kong Stadium's management company, Wembley
International, said police were usually hired in case of sporting
events.
</P>
<P>
The aim of charging was to stop people abusing the services of
police, according to a police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Under Police General Orders, "the principle governing a
decision as to whether police may be hired is that the function is
private or commercial and attracting public attendance."  
</P>
</TEXT>
