<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-more details added Chinese President Meets Australian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin, in
meeting with visiting Australian Prime Minister John Howard today,
said that China and Australia should further their cooperation
based on mutual respect and with an eye to the future.
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed the wish during a meeting with Howard here
today at the Diaoyutai State Guesthouse.
</P>
<P>
Extending a welcome to Howard, who is on his first official
visit to China as Australian Prime Minister, Jiang said he
believes that this visit is of great significance to the
development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Recalling their meeting last November in Manila during the APEC
informal summit, Jiang said that positive results came of their
talks, and stressed that continued contact between leaders of the
two sides has played an important role in deepening mutual
understanding, dissolving disputes, developing cooperation, and
guiding the direction of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Howard said he was pleased to meet with Jiang again, adding
that their meeting in Manila left him with beautiful
memories. Yesterday, he and Chinese Premier Li Peng discussed all
aspects of bilateral ties and agreed to continue expanding mutual
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Howard reiterated the Australian government's invitation for
Jiang to pay an official visit to Australia, for which Jiang
expressed appreciation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed out that a sound political relationship
constitutes a reliable guarantee for the sustained and steady
development of comprehensive Sino-Australian relations.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 25th anniversary of Sino-Australian
diplomatic relations. Jiang said that during the past 25 years,
bilateral relations have enjoyed sound development in general and
cooperation in various fields is expected to make greater progress
this year.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that the world is moving towards
multi-polarization, Jiang said that there cannot be one single
development pattern in the world.
</P>
<P>
Countries should choose their own development paths in line
with their own conditions, and develop cooperation with each other
on the basis of equality and mutual respect, Jiang said. For
disputes, he added, they should conduct consultation and
discussion, and seek common ground while reserving differences, so
as to handle the problems in a proper manner.
</P>
<P>
It is in this spirit that China handles relations with
countries whose social systems are different from that of China,
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that both China and Australia are influential countries
in the Asia-Pacific region, Jiang said that China hopes to
steadily and smoothly develop cooperative relations of mutual
benefit with Australia.
</P>
<P>
However, Jiang noted, the development of Sino-Australian
relations should not be limited to a bilateral perspective.
Instead, cooperation should be conducted with a strategic point of
view to the future and to the overall interests, and with the aim
to safeguard and promote peace, stability and prosperity in the
entire Asia-Pacific region. Thus, the two countries will make the
most of their respective advantages, and face up together to
challenges of the 21st century, he added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed that China will continue to march along the path
of building socialism with Chinese characteristics mapped out by
Comrade Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
China remains a developing country with a large population, a
weak economic foundation, and a difficult task of modernization,
Jiang said, adding that it will take long-term efforts to achieve
national prosperity.
</P>
<P>
For that, he said, China needs a stable and peaceful
international environment.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that China's economic development represents
an important contribution to peace and prosperity in the
Asia-Pacific and the world at large. The more China develops, the
more benefits it will bring to the Asia-Pacific and the world, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Australia supports China's modernization, Howard
said that with their highly complementary economies, the two
countries should develop bilateral cooperation in all fields on
the basis of mutual benefit and mutual respect for each other's
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Australia believes that China poses no threat to any country,
and that China's reform and opening-up has offered opportunities
for economic and trade cooperation for other countries, he said,
adding that Australia is willing to do more in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Also, Australia stands for an early settlement of the issue of
China's entry into the World Trade Organization, Howard said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
