<HEADLINE> Manila, Leftist Party Make Headway in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
today substantial progress has been made in its peace talks with
the leftist National Democratic Front (NDF) held last month in the
Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Howard Dee, the government's chief negotiator in the talks with
the NDF, told reporters the government is "very hopeful" to wrap
up three agreements with the NDF by June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
During the talks held in the Netherlands on March 18-24, Dee
said, the two sides were close to reaching agreement on security,
human rights and international humanitarian laws.
</P>
<P>
Dee said that one or two members of the NDF negotiating panel
might come home soon to consult their local leaders about the
on-going talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
The government panel will then go back to the Netherlands in
two weeks in a bid to complete the three agreements, he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Democratic Front, a leftist alliance led by the
Philippine Communist Party, has been engaged in armed conflict
with the government since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
During the early 1990s, some of the NDF's leaders were forced
to flee to the Netherlands after its military wing, the New
People's Army, suffered a series of major military setbacks during
its guerrilla war with the government forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
