<HEADLINE> Shanghai Holds First Animal Arts Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China's largest city of Shanghai
today kicked off its first Animal Arts Festival in the city's
Zoological Garden.
</P>
<P>
The ten-week festival centers on publicizing animal science and
culture, animal taming, animal resources development, and animal
arts creation, in an effort to educate people on protecting wild
animals and nature, said Shi Xinquan, the garden director.
</P>
<P>
More than 6,000 rare animals of 580 species will be on view for
the public.
</P>
<P>
Shi said that visitors can watch sea animal performances,
dog-taming demonstrations, and have their pictures taken with
elephants, giraffes and chimpanzees.
</P>
<P>
Visitors can also view films and TV programs about animals
during the festival.
</P>
<P>
A pet show and an art competition of animal pictures drawn by
primary and secondary students will also be held.
</P>
<P>
The festival, the first of its kind in China, will be held
annually in the 72-ha zoo, which so far has received 160 million
visitors, Shi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
