<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to File Complaint With WTO Against Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Ministry of Commerce said
today it would file a petition with the World Trade Organization
(WTO) over what it called Egypt's protectionism, the Thai news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian government demanded that all documents attached to
each shipment issued by the Thai government or agencies be further
certified by the Egyptian embassy in Thailand, the Thai embassy in
Cairo or the Egyptian foreign ministry.
</P>
<P>
These measures might be considered as disguised trade
protectionism, the news agency quoted Thai commercial counsellor
to Egypt Mongkol Somkane as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's exports failing to meet extra conditions, such as
certificates of original country, sanitary standards and details
of products, will also be banned from entering Egypt, Mongkol said.
</P>
<P>
Under international trade practices, shipments attached with
the required documents issued by the government agencies or
authorized agencies of the exporting countries are considered
justified, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mongkol accused the Egyptian government of taking the new
measures to cost Thai exporters more time and unnecessary
expenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
