<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Establish Economic Revival Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Young-sam
and opposition leaders agreed today to establish an economic
consultative body to revive the nation's sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
The council, to be composed of leaders from various walks of
life and members of the ruling and opposition parties, will map
out measures to revitalize the economy.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a joint meeting between President
Kim, major opposition National Congress for New Politics chief Kim
Dae-jung, minor opposition United Liberal Democrats leader Kim
Jong-pil and ruling New Korea Party chairman Lee Hoi-chang.
</P>
<P>
An announcement made by the four leaders after the meeting
appealed to South Koreans to share the burden of reviving the
nation's economy, saying the council will open inter-party
consultations as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The four leaders pledged to draw lessons from the recent Hanbo
scandal, hasten financial reforms and cooperate in promoting
savings and employment and stablizing wages and prices.
</P>
<P>
They promised to help small and medium-sized business groups in
solving fund shortages and encourage major corporations to take
part in international competition.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to continue negotiations on improving the real-name
financial system, foreign currency policy and other economic
issues.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the Hanbo scandal, they agreed to conduct a
thorough investigation to reveal all facts of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed that the current economic crisis basically
stemmed from public distrust in government and resulted in
socio-political unrests.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the government should regain public trust by
taking necessary measures, including clearing all suspicions
surrounding the Hanbo scandal and other issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
