<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Takes Japan to WTO Over Satellite Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC) said
today it would request formal consultations with Japan in the
World Trade Organization (WTO) on Japan's exclusion of European
suppliers from a 40-million-U.S. dollar government contract for a
global satellite navigation system.
</P>
<P>
The EC said that Japan has restricted suppliers to the use of
U.S. technical specifications, thus excluding European companies.
</P>
<P>
"The Commission considers this a serious violation of Japan's
obligations under the non-discrimination and transparency
provisions of the WTO Government Procurement Agreement," the EC
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Ministry of Transport is engaged in a Multi-
Functional Transport Satellite project aimed at launching a
satellite by 1999.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to help develop a global navigation
system for airplanes, which Japan hopes to be adapted to its
specific needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
