<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Stock Market Loses 460 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Share prices fell sharply on the
Hong Kong stock market today, hurt by drops for two consecutive
trading days on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index, the key indicator of Hong Kong's blue
chips, shed 460 points, or 3.67 percent, to close at 12,074
points, a slide that was the ninth largest in history in point
terms.
</P>
<P>
The sub-index for properties led the decline, losing 1,133
points, while finance counters dipped 446 points, utilities slid
286 points, and commerce and industry dropped 283 points.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the four-day Easter holidays, today is the first
trading day in the new financial year.
</P>
<P>
In morning trading the Hang Seng Index once broke the 12,000
mark to slip to 11,951 points, the lowest point the market has
traded the year, but bargain-hunting activities thereafter
narrowed the losses.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the plunge on the local bourse to Wall
Street's weakness. The Dow Jones industrial average lost close to
300 points for the past two trading days on heightened jitters
over the continued rise in long-term interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Measures announced last week by the Hong Kong government to
curb property prices also depressed the market, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
