<HEADLINE> Record Entry for World Short-Course Swimming Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A record-setting entry has been
registered for the World Short-course Swimming Championships
slated for mid-April in Gothenburg, Sweden, according to
information reaching here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A news release of the International Amateur Swimming Federation
 (FINA), the sport's world governing body, said that 10,608
swimmers from 77 national or regional associations have registered
for the April 17-20 championships.
</P>
<P>
Although the entry could be further enlarged as the deadline is
 April 7 at midnight for individual entry forms, it has already
beaten the previous participations -- 46 associations in the
inaugural world championships in 1993 in Palm de Mallorca, Spain
and 56 associations in the second event in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil,
 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Europe led the classifications of the participants by
continents with 35 to compete in Gothenburg, followed by 19 from
Americas, 15 from Asia, five in Africa, and three for Oceania.
</P>
<P>
As at the previous championships, a total of 32 events are set
for the four-day event, with 16 each for men's and women's
divisions, FINA said. 
</P>
