<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
today asked the people who will nominate him for another term of
office to take his age into account.
</P>
<P>
"Please take my age into account because I will be 77," the
chairman of the Indonesian National Youth Committee (KNPI),
Maulana Isman, quoted Soeharto as saying, after their meeting.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto will be 77 next year when the People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR) convenes to elect the president for the 1998-2002
term.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was responding to the committee's wish to nominate him
for another term of office.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee's proposal to nominate him could generate
assumptions among foreigners that the nomination has been
engineered to maintain the "status quo."
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government is preparing the May 29 general
election during which the three political parties -- the ruling
Golkar, the United Development Party (PPP) and the Indonesian
Democratic Party (PDI) are vying for 425 of the 500 seats of the
House of Representatives. The remaining 75 are reserved for the
armed forces, whose members do not vote in the election.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto became acting president in 1967 and assumed full
leadership the following year. In 1972, he was elected as
president by the People's Consultative Assembly which was
established by the 1971 general election.
</P>
<P>
So far, Soeharto has been elected five times.  
</P>
