<HEADLINE> Algerian Security Forces Attack Islamists' Hiding Place </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Algeria's security forces have since
last Saturday been launching a large operation against a jungle
used as a hiding place by Islamic militants, the Agence
France-Presse (AFP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The jungle is near Tizi-ouzou, 100 kilometers east of the
Algerian capital city of Algiers.
</P>
<P>
AFP quoted travelers as saying that military helicopters were
used to bomb the Islamists hiding in the Sidi Ali Bounab jungle
overlooking the communes of Naciria, Tadmait and Draa Ben-Khedda,
all of which were surrounded by the security forces.
</P>
<P>
The Sidi Ali Bounab jungle is known to be a hiding place of the
Islamists who take shelter in the dense forests there and use the
place as a base to launch terrorist attacks in Algiers.
</P>
<P>
Security forces have already launched a number of operations
there.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, security forces killed about 20 Islamists in another
operation which is still going on today in an undisclosed place,
the Algerian daily El Watan said.
</P>
<P>
Algeria's security forces have been attacking Islamic militants
since February, sometimes accompanied with bombings upon alleged
targets of Islamists in the regions of Medea in the south, Saida
and Sidi Bel Abbes in the southwest, and Tlemcen in the west.
</P>
<P>
The Algerian government has published no official reports on
the casualties of these operations, but the number of people
killed are estimated at hundreds.
</P>
<P>
Algeria will hold legislative elections on June 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
