<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Approves Emergency Humanitarian Aid for Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission (EC) said
today it would provide Albania with a package of humanitarian aid
worth 2 million ECU (about 2.28 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Some Albanians have been suffering from extreme hardship over
the past few weeks due to a crisis in Albania, which is the
poorest country in Europe.
</P>
<P>
A mission send by the European Union (EU) to Albania has found
that the people living in state institutions such as hospitals,
orphanages and homes for the elderly or the handicapped, are
suffering most.
</P>
<P>
The EC promised food, medicine and medical supplies for about
10,000 Albanians, adding that foodstuffs including wheat, rice,
sugar and pasta would be distributed to more people in need across
the country.
</P>
<P>
The aid is expected to be managed by the EC Humanitarian
Office, with the coordination of the International Committee of
the Red Cross and the Albanian Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
The EU has been deeply concerned over security problems in its
humanitarian operations in Albania after an Italian medical staff
was reportedly held hostage by unidentified rebels in the southern
port of Vlore.
</P>
<P>
The EC stressed that the supplies for Albania would be
protected from looting and the safety of relief staff must be
guaranteed. 
</P>
