<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatization Earnings Rise in Arab States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Earnings from privatization in the
Arab countries soared by almost 50 percent of the 1995 figure
thanks to their successful restructuring of the state companies.
</P>
<P>
The total revenue increased to 138 billion U.S. dollars in
1996 from 94 billion dollars in 1995, according to a report of
the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
The IMF report has been drafted by its regional bureau in the
Egyptian capital of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA) quoted today the
report by the world financial body as attributing the
phenomenal performance to the success by a big number of Arab
countries in restructuring their companies thus investors have
been attracted to purchase them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Fund sounded alarm against the spiraling
capital outflows of the Arab world, which stood at 78 billion
dollars in 1996, a 9.4 percent rise over that in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The European Union countries took the best part of the cake,
followed by the United States while some African states came the
third in this respect.
</P>
<P>
Financial inflows into the Arab countries registered only a
slight increase of 2 percent, reaching 52 billion dollars in
1996, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
