<HEADLINE> RUF Members Still Detained by Rival Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- There ''have still not been any
demand or statement'' from the breakaway Revolutionary United
Front (RUF) group which captured five top members of the rebel
movement Saturday in eastern Sierra Leone, a RUF member here said
today.
</P>
<P>
Also captured were Sierra Leone's Ambassador to Guinea Mohamed
Diaby and four Guinean security officials, Ms Agnes Deen Jalloh,
a RUF member in Freetown, disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said the men are being held at a heavily
fortified rebel base in the Kailahun district by field commanders
who back Foray Sankoh who is now under house arrest in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh was sacked by senior RUF members as the leader of the
rebel group and the commanders lured them into a trap and seized
them as hostages, earlier reports said.
</P>
<P>
According to Deen Jalloh, ''the situation is disturbing but we
hope for a settlement soon.''
</P>
<P>
''Although there has not been any direct contact, all those
captured are still alive and have not been molested,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Commission for the Consolidation of Peace
(CCP) Desmond Luke said in an interview with Xinhua, ''the
situation is being closely monitored by the governments of Sierra
Leone, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire.''
</P>
<P>
''We look forward to a breakthrough and get the peace process
back on track. This is an unfortunate development, '' he added.
</P>
<P>
The CCP was set up after the signing of the Abidjan accord
last November to monitor and work out modalities for peace in the
west African state after six years of rebel war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
