<HEADLINE> Australian Prime Minister Sees China Trip Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard said here today that his visit to China has been "highly
successful," with achievements in expanding links between the two
countries both at government and business levels.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference in the Diayutai State Guesthouse
that China and Australia have "strong, sensible relations" built
on the twin pillars of mutual interest and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
"Australia's national interests lie in sensibly and
realistically fostering these relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the highest priority of his first visit to China
as Prime Minister was to establish and strengthen personal
relations with the Chinese leaders, including Premier Li Peng and
President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
"Economic links between the two countries have been greatly
deepened and broadened as a consequence of the visit," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that members of the senior business delegation
accompanying him have established and furthered contact with their
Chinese counterparts. Bilateral economic cooperation has been
expanded from the traditional fields of primary products and
manufacturing to service industry.
</P>
<P>
He said that many aspects of Sino-Australian cooperation can be
attributed to the fact that the two countries' economies are
highly complementary. Australia has always been a strong and
reliable supplier of raw materials to China, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Australian government and the Australian
business sector will work together to pursue trade interests in
dealing with governments and businesses of other countries.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Australia does not view China as a
threat. He said that the two countries should have an effective
framework to deal with possible difficulties and differences in a
way that does not damage their broad relations. 
</P>
