<HEADLINE> First Faster Train Completes Journey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The No. 38 passenger train, the
first of China's trains to go into operation with increased speed,
arrived on schedule at 7 a.m today at the Beijing West Railway
Station, Asia's largest.
</P>
<P>
The train left Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei
Province, at 5:30 p.m. yesterday, completing the journey with a
travel time of only 13 hours and a half, about three and a half
hours less than before.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the No. 38 train has the highest rise in travel
speed. It's peak running speed reached 135 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan and Beijing are more than 1,200 km apart.
</P>
<P>
"We felt like staying at a hotel. The 'overnight" journey was
really comfortable, and it is convenient for my itinerary and
schedule," one businessman said upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
The journey is along the Beijing-Kowloon (Jingjiu) railway
line.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways said that as of today, all trains are
running at a speed of 100 km per hour on the Jingjiu, a rise of 20
km, and the figure will reach 120 km by July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
