<HEADLINE> China on the Way to Boost Flower Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Flowers have become big business
in China, as the country is on the way to becoming one of the
world's biggest flower producers and consumers.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics from the China Florists Association show that
in 1996, the demand for fresh flowers reached 1.1 billion
bouquets, 400 million more than the year before.
</P>
<P>
There are now nearly 5,000 flower shops and 670 flower markets
across the country's big cities, and a number of large wholesale
markets have emerged in Guangzhou, Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
China's total flower planting area has reached 75,000 hectares,
and the number of flower enterprises stands at 1,000, of which
more than 70 have become competitive in both the domestic and
international markets.
</P>
<P>
A computerized greenhouse has been set up in Shanghai, China's
largest city.
</P>
<P>
According to an official from the Ministry of Forestry, the
total flower output in 1996 scored 4.8 billion yuan (nearly 600
million US dollars), and the export volume reaped 80 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"By the year 2000, the total output of the flower industry will
reach 10 billion yuan, and will be one of China's fastest-growing
industries," he said.
</P>
<P>
China will hold its first flower trade fair in Shanghai on
April 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
