<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Fighting killed 147 people last
Thursday in Rumonge, southwest Burundi, during engagements between
the Tutsi-led Burundian army and Hutu rebels, reported the Agence
France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Burundian army, Colonel Isaie Nibizi, said
Monday evening that "several persons" were killed in Rumonge, in
the province of Bururi, without providing further details.
</P>
<P>
But another army officer said on condition of anonymity that
147 people were killed last Thursday during fighting between the
army and the rebels. But he failed to tell the identity of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
Other independent sources confirmed that violent fighting began
in early March in Rumonge, which extends several kilometers along
the Tanganyika Lake, according to AFP.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 150,000 people have been killed in ethnic
violences in Burundi over the past three years, reports said.
