<HEADLINE> Motorola Finances Dropouts in China's Poor Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Motorola, one of the leading US
electronics and telecommunications suppliers, today donated three
million yuan to Project Hope, a non-governmental charity that
supports millions of dropouts in China's poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
The Motorola donation will be used to set up 19 Hope schools in
underdeveloped areas and train teachers there.
</P>
<P>
Xu Yongguang, secretary general of the China Youth Development
Foundation which is responsible for promoting the project
nationwide, said at the donation ceremony that since it was kicked
off in 1989, Project Hope has helped 1.5 million children return
to school, and built more than 3,600 Hope primary schools.
</P>
<P>
Donations to the program from inside China and overseas have
amounted to about one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
He said that the project plans to expand its funding scale and
give more extensive support to the school dropouts during the next
four years, when the country will "basically resolve the poverty
problem and realize the goal of universal compulsory nine-year
education."
</P>
<P>
"We hope to get more support from both in China and overseas,
and will take good care of every donation and every project to
ensure that the donors' goodwill will be cherished and fully
realized." Xu said.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that among the school-age population
of 6 to 14-year-olds there remain 30 million youngsters who don't
go to school.
</P>
<P>
Richard Galvin, chairman of the Motorola executive committee,
said that before this donation, Motorola had poured six million
yuan into Project Hope. Such contributions to China's education
and welfare sectors will be further extended as the company
continues its long-term development in China.
</P>
<P>
At another donation ceremony here today, Motorola announced the
launching of a special scholarship in eight Chinese universities,
including the prestigious Beijing, Qinghua and Fudan universities,
and provided them with a combined two million yuan-worth of
PowerPCs, one of the most sophisticated personal computer brands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ganges Water Flow Hits Season's Low in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The water flow to Bangladesh of the
river Ganges has hit a new low during the current season and there
is no apparent sign of improvement in the availability of water,
according to Water Development Board sources.
</P>
<P>
The availability of water during the last 10-day slot of March
was not more than 12 to 13 cusecs (cubic per seconds) on an
average while as per the Ganges water sharing treaty signed on
last December Bangladesh is supposed to get an average of 29,688
cusecs per day during the period, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
On March 27 this year, the water flow at the Hardinge bridge
point was only 6,457 cusecs, while it was 9,313 cusecs on March
29, the sources said, adding the available data shows that the
water flow during these two days last year was 27,934 cusecs and
26,733 cusecs respectively.
</P>
<P>
A joint river commission official told reporters that
investigation was going on in this regard to determine why the
availability of water had fallen below the expected level.
</P>
<P>
The matter would be brought to the notice of the Indian Water
Resources Minister during his forthcoming visit to Dhaka from
April 9, the official added.
</P>
<P>
India agreed to duly share the Ganges water flow with
Bangladesh in a "historic" 30-year water sharing treaty when
Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina visited New Delhi in last
December.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
