<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Team to Scale Mt. Kurlakangri </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Japanese mountaineering team
has started on Tuesday to scale the 7,418-meter second highest
peak of Mt. Kurlakangri in China's Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The 14-people team gave up the previous plan to climb the
highest peak of the mountain before assaulting the second peak and
instead focuses on the second highest peak.
</P>
<P>
The team will plan a direct route toward the peak and hope to
complete the expedition in 50 days.
</P>
<P>
Yamamori Kinichi, the 53-year-old leader of the Japanese
members, said Japan and China begun to co-operate in the
mountaineering ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
He added that the team will put safety first in their attempt
as most of the five Japanese are over 40 years old. 
</P>
