<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Long-distance Expressway in Xinjiang Breaks Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Construction started today on the
first long-distance expressway in the northwestern Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Also the biggest World Bank-financed project in the region, the
road is expected to be completed by the end of this century. Total
cost stands at 5.2 billion yuan, including 300 million US dollars
in World Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The expressway will link the capital city of Urumqi and Kuytun,
an important industrial city in Xinjiang, running 266 kilometers
westward through the most economically-developed areas in the
autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
"The completion of the expressway will ease the heavy traffic
in Xinjiang, facilitate the cargo transportation and thereby
greatly benefit the local economy," said a World Bank official at
the ground-breaking ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The expressway is divided into fourteen sections, and eight
Chinese road construction companies and one from Brazil have won
the bid to build the road.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
