<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West African Peacekeepers in Liberia Underpaid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- West African peacekeepers operating
in Liberia, known as ECOMOG, from commander to private, are each
paid five U.S. Dollars per day, according to the Nigerian Tribune
today.
</P>
<P>
This compares with the 200-Dollar daily payment for members of
the United Nations Observer Mission in Liberia (UNOMIL).
</P>
<P>
As a result of the sharp contrast in allowances, reported
Chris Agbambu, a Nigerian Tribune correspondent who just came
back from Monrovia, the Liberian capital, the UNOMIL troops are
living in great affluence while ECOMOG soldiers just make ends
meet.
</P>
<P>
The wide disparity in allowances is also responsible for the
different attitudes of both contingents to the disarmament
process.
</P>
<P>
The UN team is said to be disposed towards longer stay in the
war-torn country, while the Nigeria-led ECOMOG has insisted on
finishing the task at hand leaving Liberia.
</P>
<P>
According to the independent daily newspaper, only a week to
the November 22, 1996 disarmament date, the UNOMIL suggested to
postpone the exercise till January 1997.
</P>
<P>
But ECOMOG Commander Major-General Victor Maly insisted to go
ahead even by ECOMOG itself if the UN mission was not ready,
because "the six West African countries that make up ECOMOG are
not as comfortable as they (UNOMIL) are in Liberia," it said,
quoting the Nigerian general.
</P>
<P>
To date, disarmament of Liberia's more than 30,000 former
factional fighters has been completed successfully, and the
country's general and presidential elections will be held on May
30 as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the UNOMIL will extend its stay in Liberia until
after the May 30 polls so that it can monitor the elections
together with the Organization of African Unity and the Economic
Community of West African States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
