<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Adopts 1997 Investment Priorities Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government today
approved the 1997 Investment Priorities Plan, which is aimed at
further boosting the economy.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos gave the go-signal for the plan "subject
to some refinements in certain areas following the discussions
during this afternoon's cabinet meeting," the presidential palace
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The plan contains 32 areas of preferred economic activities,
including export industries, manufacturing, agriculture, food and
forestry, textiles, chemical products, infrastructure development,
environment protection and mining, it said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 32 areas, the presidential palace said, 28 are carried
over from the 1996 plan. The four new inclusions are feeds
production, pulp and paper, book publishing and fish production,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Investments in the Philippines last year rose to 490 billion
pesos (18.6 billion U.S. dollars), an increase of 20 percent over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The government attributed the increase to the favorable
investment climate in the country and the surging economy.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has scaled down its investment growth
target of this year to 13 percent, almost 3 percentage points
below the 1996 target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Foreign Debt Likely to Hit Record High in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign debt in 1997
is predicted to reach 144.4 billion U.S. dollars, surpassing
Mexico's 1994 figure in a foreign debt crisis, a private research
institute said today.
</P>
<P>
The Hyundai Research Institute predicted that the country's
foreign debt for this year would increase 30.1 percent over last
year and account for 25-30 percent of the gross domestic product
(GDP).
</P>
<P>
The institute said that a sharp rise in foreign debt is likely
to cause price hikes and heavier debt-servicing burden as well as
a serious foreign exchange crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Korea had earlier forecast that the country's
foreign debt in 1997 would reach 140.4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Korea Institute of Finance also warned of a foreign
exchange crisis resulting from a rapid capital outflow.
</P>
<P>
It said that the rising current-account deficit and growing
ratio of short-term debt are likely to increase the possibility of
a temporary but sharp capital outflow designed to sidestep foreign
exchange risk.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Mexico's foreign debt totaled 136.5 billion dollars,
representing 35 percent of the GDP, while its foreign currency
reserves stood at 6.44 billion dollars, leading to a serious
foreign exchange crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Korea Institute of Finance said that with the continuing
devaluation of the Korean won, the high growth rate of local
currency and dwindling foreign exchange reserves, South Korea has
been close to a foreign exchange crisis.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government is expected to take measures to
avoid a foreign exchange crisis similar to that in Mexico, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
However, experts said that the country's economy could face
difficulties if banking institutions are saddled with huge loans
in the course of the rise and fall of the economic bubble arising
from currency expansion.
</P>
<P>
They suggested that the government take measures to cut back on
import and reduce the current-account deficit so as to revive the
national economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
