<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Slow in Transfer to Environment-friendly Fuel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is trailing Europe in
the introduction of liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) as an
alternative fuel for vehicles, Hong Kong Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The technology had been used for more than 40 years in Europe,
Ho Kwong-wai, assistant director of Electrical and Mechanical
Services, said.
</P>
<P>
Ho is a member of an Environmental Protection Department-led
task force which studies the use of LPG to reduce air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The task force is considering a plan to phase out Hong Kong's
18,000 diesel taxis and replace them with more expensive LPG-run
vehicles, he said.
</P>
<P>
The particles emitted from vehicles would be reduced by 30
percent and engine noise level also lowered if the plan succeeded.
</P>
<P>
But the plan may be strongly opposed by taxi operators and
drivers because of the capital cost.
</P>
<P>
The government will conduct a pilot scheme using 20 brand-new
LPG-run taxis early next year, and the task force will look into
the reaction of drivers and passengers, and the incentives that
can be introduced during the one-year trial.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
