<HEADLINE> South-South Cooperation Center to Be Set up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto is
expected to realize the establishment of a NAM (Non-Aligned
Movement) center for south-south technical cooperation soon in
Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, a senior official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Nana Sutresna, presidential aide for Non-Aligned Movement (NAM)
affairs, said the establishment of NAM's center for south-south
cooperation was a joint project of Indonesia and Brunei
Darussalam.
</P>
<P>
"If south countries succeed in development, their economies
will invariably grow more rapidly so that they will also be able
to develop themselves and no longer need aid from western donor
countries or the World Bank," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said President Soeharto wished to create a new face of NAM
member countries which have been concentrating on economic
development to realize the Bandung principles to live in peaceful
co-existence.
</P>
<P>
The presence of the center, he added, was expected to help
south countries which are still in need of technical and financial
assistance in carrying out development.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto proposed to form the center in 1995 at the
ministerial conference of the NAM Coordinating Bureau in Bandung,
West Java.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
