<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Impose Measures to Control Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Tough measures to control
water usage, which tighten up on the consumption of households
and local authorities, are set to become law within months, local
daily "The Star" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the National Water Supply Regulations proposed by the
Water Affairs Department, people are banned to water gardens,
sports fields or lawns between October and March.
</P>
<P>
There will be a nationwide and total ban on hosing down
pavements or any other hardened area, which, the report said,
would put the businesses that use high-powered hoses to clean
fouled pavements daily in a very difficult position.
</P>
<P>
In addition, local authorities will also have to comply with
the regulations, and will no longer be allowed to water public
gardens and lawns during the hot part of the day in summer.
</P>
<P>
Other regulations include a ban on installing a shower head
with a maximum flow rate of more than 10 liters a minute, and car
washes will have to ensure that 70 percent of water is recycled.
</P>
<P>
Neil Macleod, chairman of the National Water Regulations
Drafting Committee, said many South African people are used to
using water as if this were a water-rich country.
</P>
<P>
"We urgently need to change people's behavior from a
free-and-easy approach of using as much water as they like",
Macleod said, stressing that "we are an arid country, comparable
with Israel, and these regulations are the first step in a
national process to conserve water".
</P>
<P>
"In about five years we will have to introduce stringent
regulations, such as tariff hikes and compelling people to fit
water-saving devices," Macleod said.
</P>
<P>
He said the old Water Act of 1956 will be replaced by two new
acts, the Water Services Act and the Water Resources Act, which
are due to go before parliament this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
