<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, South Africa to Hold Crucial Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Trade ministers of Zimbabwe and
South Africa will meet here this week to discuss outstanding
issues that may pave the way to the long-awaited replacement of
the obsolete 1964 trade pact and freer trade between the two
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily "The Herald" today, Zimbabwe's Minister
of Industry and Commerce Nathan Shamuyarira said yesterday that
South African Minister of Trade and Industry Alec Irwin is
scheduled to arrive on Thursday for the crucial trade talks.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will consolidate progress made by three committees
that were tasked to look into the protracted trade negotiations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Shamuyarira said significant progress had been made so far by
two of the committees that will be discussed at the meeting.
Another committee has not made much headway.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will center on the agreement on agricultural
products and other products. The latter include heavy machinery,
spare parts and motor vehicles. 
</P>
