<HEADLINE> Adoption of Amendment Bill Momentous Occasion: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan said here today the adoption of the 13th amendment bill
by both houses of the parliament in one day is a momentous
occasion.
</P>
<P>
Giving his reaction in the parliament house, he said it was
significant that both the National Assembly and the Senate passed
the bill unanimously.
</P>
<P>
The new bill would help strengthen democratic institutions and
put democracy on a proper path, he said.
</P>
<P>
It would also lend continuity to institutions which would
result in proper development planning, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Minister said that over the past ten years, four
assemblies were dissolved which created uncertainty in political
institutions and disrupted planning programs.
</P>
<P>
The bill, he said, would put an end to uncertainty and also
slam the door on those who try to get into power through backdoor
or intrigue.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign secretary level talks with India, Ayub Khan said
these were a beginning.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to talk, we talk from a position of strength
because of the massive mandate given to the government by the
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question, he said he would be visiting the United
States in May.
</P>
<P>
Answering another question, he said Pakistan would soon post a
new ambassador in Russia and later he would visit Moscow.
</P>
<P>
He said the Prime Minister's visit might take place afterwards.
</P>
<P>
"We want to have good dialogue with Russia as it has a great
trade potential," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
