<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Weeds Lead to Huge Food Crop Losses in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- About seven billion U.S. dollars
worth of agricultural produce is destroyed in Africa every year
by genus striga, a parasitic weed which damages food crops,
according to a research report.
</P>
<P>
The report of the Nigeria-based International Institute for
Tropical Agriculture (IITA), which is made known today, said that
as many as 30 to 35 known species of the striga are present in
west and central Africa.
</P>
<P>
To effectively control the weeds, inexpensive remedial
measures, tailored to the needs of African cropping system, must
be developed, it suggests.
</P>
<P>
According to IITA, traditional African cropping systems, which
include prolonged fallow, rotations and inter-cropping, encourage
the breeding of the weeds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
