<HEADLINE> Major Remains Ready for TV Debate With Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John Major
said on Tuesday he was still willing to go for a TV election
debate with Labor Party leader Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
"We the Conservative Party have accepted the terms of the
broadcasters' proposals as they stand even though they are not
perfect from our point of view," Major said in a campaign news
conference.
</P>
<P>
Major accepted an election debate with Blair on March 16 after
the latter requested repeatedly for such an American-style
televised campaign. But the debate seems running to a dead end
after the two parties were at loggerheads over formation of the
debate.
</P>
<P>
"Turkeys may not vote for Christmas, but chickens apparently
run away from broadcasters," Major said.
</P>
<P>
Labor Party enjoys at least a 20-point lead in the opinion
polls and seems set to topple the Conservative Party which has
ruled Britain over the past 18 years in the May election.
</P>
<P>
But political analysts believe Blair has little to win from the
televised debate, which would be the first in British electoral
history, while Major has nothing to lose. 
</P>
</TEXT>
