<HEADLINE> WNBF Leader Flees to Khartoum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Juma Oris, Ugandan rebel leader
of the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF), has fled to Sudanese capital
of Khartoum, "The New Vision" reported here today.
</P>
<P>
He was wounded on March 12 in an ambush launched by Sudan
People's Liberation Army (SPLA). But he survived the ambush and
managed to reach southern Sudanese city of Juba.
</P>
<P>
Security officers here failed to identify the reason why
Sudanese sent the rebel leader to their capital.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports from southern Sudan said the fighting between
the SPLA and the government troops of Sudan is carried out some
55 kilometers south-west of Juba, south Sudan, and the SPLA is
systematically closing to the city from all directions.
</P>
<P>
Sam Caku, another WHBF leader, who is deputy political
commissar, arrived Khartoum earlier.
</P>
<P>
But Abdallatif Tia, still another WNBF rebel leader, is held
by the SPLA with his 518 subordinates.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA were to hand over the captured rebels to the Ugandan
authorities through the International Committee of Red Cross, but
Uganda asked the SPLA to hand over them directly.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the Ugandan army killed 13, captured
eight rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) in western
Kasese district last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The ADF had some 1,000 soldiers in its ranks last November,
but the the main forces of ADF were annihilated in later
operations launched by the government troops and its remaining
forces devided into small groups scattered in the west and
southwest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
