<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Patriot's 100-Year-Old Wish Finally Comes True (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- When Lin Zexu, a patriotic lord of
the Qing Dynasty (1368-1644), resisted British attempts to force
opium on the Chinese. His official career ended in disgrace, but
now his wish of over a century ago will come true this July.
</P>
<P>
In 1839, when Britain forced China to become hooked on opium,
Lin, who was an imperial commissioner, led the move to ban opium
in the south China city of Guangzhou, and destroyed some 20,000
cases of opium seized from the British. In retaliation, the
British colonialists, reacting to the ban on the opium trade,
invaded China with their naval vessels and armed forces, starting
the Opium War.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the court of the Qing Dynasty was defeated and was
forced to cede Hong Kong to the British.
</P>
<P>
Lin Zexu, who was regarded as far-sighted and patriotic by some
Western critics, was exiled to northwestern China's Xinjiang by
the ineffectual Qing government.
</P>
<P>
A century later, Lin Zexu's great great-grandson, Ling Qing,
who served as Chinese ambassador to the United Nations in the
1980s, acting with his British counterpart, submitted the
Sino-British Joint Declaration, stating that China would resume
the exercise of its sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1, 1997, to
the UN deputy secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
"This is a historical coincidence," Ling Qing noted, explaining
that "China can take back Hong Kong and fulfil my ancestor's
wish at the same time, mainly because our country is becoming
prosperous and stronger."
</P>
<P>
On a hillside in Fuzhou, the capital of east China's Fujian
Province, one can find Lin's tomb. His great-great-grandson said
poignantly, "The Lin family members have always come to worship
our ancestors every Pure and Bright Festival. The return of Hong
Kong to the embrace of the motherland on July 1 of this year will
finally accomplish the wish of our ancestor."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
