<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Patriot's 100-Year-Old Wish Finally Comes True (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ling Qing is a descendant of Lin Gongshu, Lin Zexu's third
son. His father, Lin Busui, served as an official of the court of
late Qing Dynasty and in the goverment of the Northern
Warlords. Ling took part in the War of Resistance against Japanese
Aggression, and was involved in political activities and foreign
affairs. At that time he changed his name from Lin Moqing.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of the People's Republic of China, Ling
became one of the first generation of new Chinese diplomats and
was a witness to the tremendous changes that took place in Chinese
society, economy, and foreign affairs. And he became Chinese
ambassador to the UN in 1980.
</P>
<P>
Ling said that new China has gained extensive recognition and
respect from the world community, and is playing a more important
role in international affairs, especially since the reform and
opening-up.
</P>
<P>
It is because of this that Hong Kong can be returned smoothly
to the motherland, he noted.
</P>
<P>
As a veteran diplomat, Ling believes that a major factor for
the smooth resolution is the "one country, two systems" concept,
and says that Hong Kong's smooth transition will certainly succeed
and that Hong Kong will become more prosperous and stable after
the return.
</P>
<P>
The 74-year-old Ling is now vice-chairman of the Subcommittee
of Foreign Affairs of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference National Committee. Whenever he returns to his hometown
of Fuzhou, he goes to Lin Zexu's birth place, the old family
house, and to the tomb to recall his ancestor's deeds.
</P>
<P>
These historic relics should be maintained to remind people of
China's poverty and disgrace in the past, and enable them to carry
forward the staunch spirit of the older generation to resist
foreign agression, Ling says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German President Arrives for State Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 1 (Xinhua) -- German President Roman
Herzog arrived here today for a five-day state visit to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
The German leader is being accompanied by a 100-member
delegation including former soccer maestro Franz Beckenbauer for
his first official visit here.
</P>
<P>
He was accorded a red-carpet welcome upon his arrival at the
Kuala Lumpur International Airport and was then whisked away to
Parliament Square here for the official welcoming ceremony where
he was received by Malaysian King Tuanku Ja'afar and Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir is scheduled to call on Herzog tomorrow afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow morning, Herzog is scheduled to attend a coaching
session of the Malaysian youth soccer team here by Beckenbauer,
who is now Bayern Munich FC president.
</P>
<P>
Herzog wraps up his state visit with a trip to Sarawak, East
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Germany is Malaysia's leading European trade partner after
Britain. Malaysia, in turn, is Germany's third largest trade
partner in Southeast Asia after Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries increased from 3.33 billion
ringgit (about 1.332 billion US dollars) in 1987 to 12.728 billion
ringgit (about 5.0912 billion US dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is also an increasingly popular destination for
German tourists whose arrivals have more than doubled from 28,000
in 1987 to over 80,000 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Investment by German companies in Malaysia is expected to
surge to 6 billion ringgit (about 2.4 billion US dollars) in the
next two years against about 1.617 billion ringgit (about 646.8
million US dollars) from Germany already invested in Malaysia for
the period 1980 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
The German president will proceed to Japan after his five-day
visit to Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
