MACAO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Macao Government has lifted a
19-month ban on the import of migrant labor for the textile and
garment-making industry.
</P>
<P>
A government gazette published on Monday says that all those
textile and garment-making factories intending to hire migrant
workers from outside Macao can apply between April 15 and April
30.
</P>
<P>
Textile and garment-making accounts for more than 70 percent of
 the exports of Macao.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was greeted with mixed reaction as factory
owners and trade unions still disagree on the import of migrant
labor.
</P>
<P>
Many factory owners applauded the resumption of import of
migrant labor, saying that they have suffered losses due to severe
shortage of workers.
</P>
<P>
They also urged the government to lift ban on migrant workers
which are needed by some other economic sectors such as hotels and
restaurants so as to push local economy out of the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
But local trade unions complained that the coming of migrant
labor will aggravate the jobless rate, saying the government has
not done enough in the training of local labor and that more than
7,000 people are still out of job.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the jobless rate dropped to 3.4
percent during the period between December 1996 and February
1997. It hit the highest of 4.6 percent last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
