<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Wipe Out Leprosy by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Leprosy is to be eradicated in
Vietnam by the turn of the century, official reports said here
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports of the Institute of Dermatology,
Vietnam is one of the 80 countries in the world with a high
proportion of lepers.
</P>
<P>
Since late 1995, patients detected in the country have been
given proper treatment with the majority cured completely.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 63 lepers per 100,000 persons at the
national level and 17 of the 61 provinces still have 121 to 383
leprosy patients per 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has a population of more than 70 million.
</P>
<P>
The number of lepers detected in a single year declined to
4,743 in 1996 from 36,616 in 1983.
</P>
<P>
To eradicate the disease by the year 2000, leprosy awareness
are to be disseminated throughout the country to encourage people
to voluntarily have check-ups and treatment with the governmental
public health sector acting as the driving force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
