<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation in March Estimated at 4.4 Percent in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The inflation rate for March in the
Philippines will settle at 4.4 percent, the same level of last
month, Economic Development Secretary Cielito Habito said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Habito attributed the expected low-level inflation to stability
of food prices and lower prices of petroleum products in the
month.
</P>
<P>
"There was nothing extraordinary that would deviate the
inflation significantly both on month-on-month and year-on-year,"
Habito said.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate in February hit an all-time low for 10 years at
4.4 percent, the second time since last September, despite the
recent wage adjustment and the full deregulation of the oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
Habito traced the lower-than-expected inflation to the
government's efficiency in ensuring price increase commensurate to
the actual cost increases.
</P>
<P>
He said economic planners, however, expect the inflation rate
to go up slightly during the second half of the year, as a result
of higher inflation during the same period of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
