<HEADLINE> Silk Found In Ming Tomb At East China Seaport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Silk has been found in a tomb from
the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) in Quanzhou city, in east China's
Fujian province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists said this is the first find of this sort
in the city even though it was the starting point of the ancient
marine silk route.
</P>
<P>
The silk was in a 412-year-old tomb of Ding Wei, an imperial
minister of the Ming Dynasty, and his two wives.
</P>
<P>
Ding was wearing a white Islamic hat and a costume in the the
style of Han dynasty (206 BC-AD 220), suggesting a mixed culture
of different nationalities.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, there was finely wrought gold lace on the
skirt of Ding's first wife and the head ornaments of his second
wife. 
</P>
</TEXT>
