<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Percent Consumption Tax Becomes Effective in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Prices for almost all goods and
services sold in Japan went up as the consumption tax rose for the
first time to five percent today.
</P>
<P>
The tax had been three percent since its introduction in April
1989. Half of the two percentage point increase is to be levied as
a local consumption tax.
</P>
<P>
Coupled with the termination of two trillion Japanese yen worth
of special reductions in income and residential taxes, taxpayers
are expected to end up in paying seven trillion yen in additional
taxes in fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to Finance Ministry calculations, the increased
consumption tax burden on a family of four with a yearly income of
seven million yen (56,900 U.S. dollars) will come to roughly
67,000 yen (544 U.S. dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
But some private think tanks have put the figure higher, and
concerns remain that the increased tax burden could dampen
consumers' spending during the first half of fiscal 1997 and lower
economic growth figures for the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The government's economic forecast, released in December, took
into account the probability of a slowdown in growth due to the
tax changes and put real growth for fiscal 1997 at 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, consumers' rush to buy goods ahead of the tax hike was
generally less than anticipated, and officials at the Finance
Ministry and the Economic Planning Agency (EPA) predicted that
spending during the April-June months will not slacken as much as
initially feared.
</P>
<P>
One EPA official said that while there were signs of
last-minute purchases of relatively expensive items, such as homes
and automobiles, in the months preceding the tax hike, it was not
as marked as the shopping spree seen on the eve of the
introduction of the consumption tax eight years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: Impact of Pollution by Gulf War Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The long-term effect on human
health by air pollution caused by oil-well flames during the 1991
Gulf War needs to be monitored, a senior official of a Kuwaiti
environment body said.
</P>
<P>
Saleh Al-Muzaini, director of the Environmental Sciences
Department at the Kuwait Institute for Scientific Research
(KISR), made the remarks in his exclusive interview with the
local daily Arab Times, which was published today.
</P>
<P>
He said the studies by the environmental department showed "a
diminishing of the atmospheric pollution has been observed after
the oil fires were extinguished, but the effects of exposure on
human health needs to be monitored carefully through properly
designed epidemiological studies."
</P>
<P>
He said his department had so far completed about 24 critical
research projects while detailed studies on 19 other projects
were underway.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the oil-soaked soil remediation, he said
biotechnological studies had been conducted for detoxification
and effective utilization of nearly 20 million tonnes of
oil-impregnated sand.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, "Bioremediation efforts for the clean-up of the
oil contaminated desert soil in Kuwait are promising in our
laboratory tests," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the environment official said an analysis of the dust
samples at present in comparison with post-war ones "might show
contamination with hazardous chemicals," but no prediction could
be made about its toxicity as their effects could be observed
only after a long period.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf War resulted in one of the worst environmental
catastrophes in the history of the mankind. About 6 to 8 million
barrels of crude oil were released into the sea as well as the
desert areas in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Around 800 oil wells in Kuwait remained burning for several
months emitting huge quantities of pollutants to the atmosphere,
and 60 million barrels of crude oil gushed from the burning
wells, thus creating oil pools over a vast area of the desert
land.
</P>
<P>
The KISR organized an international conference last November
to study and exchange information about the long-term effects of
the Gulf War on the environment in the Gulf region and other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Presentations made at the conference showed that progress in
the understanding of many aspects of the impact of the Gulf War
on the environment has been made.
</P>
<P>
But the fact that conclusive statements regarding long-term
effects are still premature was shared by participants of the
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
