<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Supports Arab League's Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia expressed
support for resolutions adopted at Arab League ministerial
conference that called on the Arab states to freeze relations with
the Jewish state to press it scrap its settlement policy.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi cabinet in a meeting Monday night condemned the
Israeli practices and asserted that settlement policy constituted
violations of the Middle East peace process launched in Madrid in
1991, Saudi Press Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet especially denounced Israel's construction of a
new Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem and warned that such
"policies would result in dangerous effects on the peace
process."
</P>
<P>
Arab foreign ministers held a two-day meeting in Cairo and
adopted a resolution at the end of the meeting Monday night to
reactivate the economic boycott of Israel, stop normalization
steps, close Israeli offices and missions and pull out of
multilateral talks on aspects of Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has vowed to press
ahead with the construction of the settlement defying the
world-wide criticism of the move.
</P>
<P>
Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz has condemned the Israeli plans,
saying that the Israeli policy on Jerusalem is "tantamount to
abrogation of international conventions and Security Council
resolutions."
</P>
<P>
King Fahd also urged the international community to coerce
Israel into stopping the construction of settlements in the
occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia does not maintain any official relations with
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
