<HEADLINE> Chinese Manufacturer Delivers 500th Boeing 737 Part </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A leading Chinese aircraft
manufacturer completed its 500th vertical stabilizer for the
Boeing 737-300 recently.
</P>
<P>
This means that the cooperation between the Xi'an Aircraft
Industrial (Group) Co. Ltd. (XAIC) and the American company has
entered a new period, according to officials of the two companies
who attended a delivery ceremony in Xi'an, capital of northwest
China's Shaanxi province.
</P>
<P>
The Xi'an company is a development and production base of
medium-size and large aircraft and has cooperated extensively with
foreign businesses since China adopted its reform and opening-up
policy in late 1978.
</P>
<P>
In April 1984, XAIC agreed to produce Boeing 737-300 vertical
stabilizers. The 7.3-m by 3.3-m part weighs 370 kg and consists of
more than 1,200 smaller parts. It is the biggest part on Boeing's
commercial planes that is produced outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
To guarantee quality, XAIC spent 300 million yuan on a
large-scale overhaul of its production facilities and to improve
its quality control system. It completed its first stabilizer in
March 1988.
</P>
<P>
The parts have all met Boeing's quality standards, said an XAIC
official, and the localization rate of the parts is 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
In commenting on the quality of XAIC's products, Boeing said
that it will further expand cooperation with the Chinese partner,
including establishing joint ventures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
