<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Controversial Portions of Eighth Amendment Scrapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Senate today
unanimously adopted the Constitution's 13th Amendment Act 1997
scrapping controversial portions of the Eighth Amendment of the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The bill passed by 79 votes in favor while none against
encompasses the annulment of Article 58-2 (b) divesting the
president of his powers to dissolve the National Assembly and
dismiss the government.
</P>
<P>
The portions of the Amendment which had taken days to be
adopted was scrapped in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
The clause had empowered the president to dissolve the assembly
when "a situation has arisen in which the government of the
federation cannot be carried on in accordance with the provisions
of the Constitution and an appeal to the electorate is necessary."
</P>
<P>
The bill also amends Article 101 of the Constitution regarding
the appointment of provincial governors. The governors would now
be appointed on the advice of the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The bill also amended Article 112 of the Constitution taking
away powers of the governor to dissolve the provincial assembly in
circumstances where a provincial government could not be carried
on in accordance with the provisions of the Constitution and an
appeal to the electorate was necessary.
</P>
<P>
Through an amendment to the Article 243 of the Constitution,
the new bill withdraws the powers of the president to appoint "in
his discretion" the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff
Committee and Service Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
The Eighth Amendment to the Constitution was made in 1985
during the regime of late President Zia-ul Haq and it has been
used four times ever since.
</P>
<P>
General Zia-ul Haq dissolved the National Assembly on 29th of
May in 1988. President Ghulam Ishaq Khan dismissed Benazir
Bhutto's Government on August 6, 1990 and Nawaz Sharif's
Government on April 18, 1993. Benazir Bhutto's Government again
fell victim to this amendment on November 5, 1996 and the action
of the President was upheld by the Supreme Court on Jan. 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 08:57 </DATE_TIME>
