<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Official Decries Effects of SAPs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A trade union official has urged
the Kenyan government to fight against commercialization and
consumerism being promoted by Western countries, according to a
Kenya Times report today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted Boniface Munyao, deputy
secretary-general of the Central Organization of Trade Unions
(COTU), as saying on Monday that the economic ideologies of
Structural Adjustment Programs (SAPs) are totally foreign to the
African continent.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the effects of the SAPs and other economic
adjustments imposed by Western countries are already felt by
Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
"Already we see the commercialization and consumerism of
everything in the country," said the trade union official, adding
that these two things are terrible to the African communal life.
</P>
<P>
He argued that this is not the right time for restructuring
jobs and employment since the economy has not yet taken off well.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "some of the ideologies brought to us in
essence are meant to stifle us in order not to match them."
</P>
<P>
Munyao pointed out that some leaders in the country only saw
good in the SAPs and not the effects on the ordinary workers and
common people.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the future of the country's economy is bleak if
the economic ideologies imposed by Western countries are fully
followed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
