<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM on Relations with China (Part 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China's cooperation and close relationship with ASEAN will not
only be beneficial to both sides, but also contribute to the
stability of the Asia-Pacific region, he said.
</P>
<P>
China became a dialogue partner to ASEAN in July 1996 and it is
also a participant in the ASEAN regional forum, Chavalit said,
adding that Thailand is pleased with these because the links will
serve as bridges between China and ASEAN members.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said that geopolitically speaking, China, now a close
neighbor of ASEAN, will be adjacent to the grouping when Myanmar,
Laos and Cambodia join ASEAN in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Relations between China and ASEAN will be even closer, when
land and waterway transport networks are linked within the
framework of the quadrangle growth area. The networks are expected
to play an important role in strengthening the economic links
between China and ASEAN, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On Thailand's trade links with Hong Kong after July 1, 1997,
Chavalit said, the handover ceremony at midnight of June 30 will
be an important event in China's history.
</P>
<P>
He believed that the handover will help build confidence of the
international community in Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Thai government is confident in Hong Kong's
future, believing that the Chinese government will be able to
maintain Hong Kong's stability and prosperity, as well as its
status as an international trade and financial center.
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to China, Chavalit said, trade between
Thailand and Hong Kong will not be adversely affected, but will
instead grow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
