<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 08:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Privatization Victims Obtain Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Victims of Turkey's privatization
drive received a total compensation of 4.12 million U.S. dollars
over the past years, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Out of 4,692 employees, 4,360 applied for compensation after
losing their jobs due to the privatization program and received
the money.
</P>
<P>
Most of the 291.7 million dollars obtained from the
privatization of the state-owned industries is reserved to
increase employment, investment and to pay the debts of the
state-run economic enterprises, the paper quoted financial
sources here as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the "Working Power Adaptation Project", which is
being carried out by the Treasury and aimed at creating new jobs
for the unemployed, is reportedly proceeding smoothly.
</P>
<P>
The project, with the support of the World Bank, is of great
significance because it will not only solve the thorny problem
of unemployment in the country but also increase regional
economic development, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
The same sources pointed out that the process privatization
should be coordinated with relevant employment measures so as to
decrease the negative effects to the society, because the process
itself is likely to increase unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The privatization process started in 1984 in Turkey but it
slowed down following the death of former president Turgut Ozal
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Turkey made great strides early this year by selling the
shares of the three banks of Etibank, Anadolubank and Denizbank,
with a total value of 342.5 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The drive, however, has drawn sharp criticism from trade
unions which described the government as ignoring the interests
of civil servants and workers and trying to plunder the state
assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
