<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Developing Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The capital of central China's Hubei
Province is developing tourism resources and improving facilities
to promote the tourism business.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan is building two scenic zones around Donghu Lake and
Daoguan River, and a holiday zone around Mulan Lake in the urban
area.
</P>
<P>
On the outskirts, an agricultural tourist program is being
developed, so is a wildlife park where visitors can go
sight-seeing and hunting, and hold cook-outs.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan plans to build two more five-star hotels and five
four-star hotels in the next few years, which will add 3,000 more
hotel rooms. It will also build more lower-level hotels and
renovate some that are not as good to accommodate more tourists.
</P>
<P>
This city on the Yangtze River plans to have both local and
long-distance water tours. The longest will go to Chongqing in the
west and Shanghai on the east coast, where the Yangtze enters the
East China Sea.
</P>
<P>
Special tourist trains will connect Wuhan with such famous
tourist sites as the Three Gorges, Mount Wudang, and Mount Lushan.
</P>
<P>
It is also developing regulations on managing the tourism
business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
