<HEADLINE> Ugandan Refugees in Southern Sudan in Critical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 2,000 Ugandan refugees in
southern Sudan are in critical condition due to the fighting
between the government troops of Sudan and Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA), local press "The New Vision" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
"We have reports that women and children are starving in the
bushes as they are looking for any available means to return to
Uganda. Many others feared dead," an United Nations official
asked to be not named told the newspaper Sunday in Arua,
north-western Uganda.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Local Government Ministry said their
colleagues and UN High Commissioner for Refugees officials
visited southern Sudan and western Zaire last week confirmed the
report and urged Ugandan refugees scattered in these areas to
return to their home.
</P>
<P>
There are some 8,000 Ugandan refugees in camps in southern
Sudan and the West Nile Bank Front Rebels tried to stop the
refugees to return, a security official in West Nile Region,
north-western Uganda said. The WNBF uses the camps as the recruit
bases, he added.
</P>
<P>
But still, call for return received a warm reaction among
refugees. Some 250 Ugandan refugees returned to north-western
Uganda on Sunday after a 18-year of exile in Zaire and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The fighting between the Sudanese army and the SPLA is now
carried out 55 kilometers from Juba, southern Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
