<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Considering Visit to Washington: Radio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu is considering making a visit to the United States soon
to seek ways of resolving the Israeli-Palestinian crisis, Israel
Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is expected to decide today whether he would make
such a visit, which seems to be important to break the current
impasse in the peace process and the rising tension.
</P>
<P>
The radio reported that Netanyahu would probably visit
Washington between Sunday and Tuesday before traveling to
the Netherlands for an official visit.
</P>
<P>
Top on Netanyahu's agenda in Washington will be the
arrangement of a summit with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
As the leading mediator in the peace process, the U.S. is
currently launching a new round of diplomatic activities to bridge
the Israeli-Palestinian gap. U.S. President Bill Clinton sent his
Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross to the Mideast last week on a
mediation tour.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli President Ezer Weizman, the ceremonial head
of state, is also making efforts to try to ease the current
tension. Arye Shumer, Director-General of the President's Office,
met Monday with PNA Culture and Information Minister Yasser Abed
Rabbo in a Jerusalem hotel to discuss the possibility of holding
a meeting between Arafat and Weizman or Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Weizman was the leading force in arranging the first
Netanyahu-Arafat meeting early last September, and he himself met
last October with Arafat following the late September bloodshed
which killed 75 people.
</P>
<P>
Following the resolution approved Monday in Cairo by the Arab
Foreign Ministers meeting to freeze ties with Israel, Weizman
called for resumption of Israeli-Palestinian talks which have
been stalled since Israel decided to build the Abu Ghneim (Har
Homa) settlement in East Jerusalem last month.
</P>
<P>
This morning, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
traveled to Washington on an official visit at the invitation
of his U.S. counterpart William Cohen to discuss bilateral
military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The trip, scheduled a week ago, was delayed due to the current
tension. Mordechai will also meet with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to review regional strategic situation and the
Israeli-Palestinian tension.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
