<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University Students Should Be Self-Reliant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior official has urged that
Chinese university students should rely on their own strength
instead of constantly seeking financial help from other people.
</P>
<P>
Gao Hong, deputy secretary-general of the All-China Students
Federation, said that the federation will continue to aid those
students experiencing financial difficulties, but "we should first
encourage them to face hardships boldly and independently,"
according to a "China Youth Daily" report.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the paper, Gao said that self-reliance is
the basic requirement for a student who wants to contribute to the
country in the next century -- when the social and international
competition will be strong.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that university students take part in part-time
study/part-time work programs, clean up dormitories and restrooms
by themselves, and do more social work, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Gao said that the campaign to aid poor students would go
through three stages: the first is to accumulate social funding to
help them complete study; the second is to encourage them to be
self-reliant; the third is to ask them to connect their personal
goals with the country's needs.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990s, China abolished the old system under which the
state covered all tuition fees for university students; all
students now must pay the fees themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
