<HEADLINE> Non-Farming Sector Booms in Northwest China Countryside </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Non-agricultural industries have
seen substantial development in the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region
of northwest China,
</P>
<P>
Now grain processing, retail sales, transportation, commerce
and catering industries contribute 45 percent to Ningxia's annual
rural output value, up 14 percent from 1990.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, the autonomous region has restructured the
rural economy by focusing on non-farm industries, providing more
employment opportunities for surplus rural laborers.
</P>
<P>
Various commodity production bases for grain, potatoes,
oil-bearing crops, and medicinal herbs have been set up in recent
years, generating an output value of 4.9 billion yuan (590.4
million US dollars) in 1996, four times the 1990 figure.
</P>
<P>
At present, the number of rural marketplaces is 300, with a
turnover climbing 33 percent annually. The fast growth has pushed
development of the farming sector in Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Ningxia's grain output was 2.58 million tons and
farmers' annual per-capita income reached 1,416 yuan, 19.7 percent
more than the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuzhou Streamlines Joint Ventures Administration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 1 (Xinhua) -- In Fuzhou, capital of south
China's Fujian Province, a new administrative method to evaluate
foreign-funded ventures is as simple as the ABC's.
</P>
<P>
As part of the local government's effort to guide the inflow of
overseas investment, and to support development of pillar
industries, foreign-funded ventures will be divided into three
basic categories.
</P>
<P>
Fuzhou has seen a substantial increase in foreign investment in
recent years, reaching 10.5 billion US dollars in contractual
value by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The combined output value of the 2,249 joint ventures in
operation has reached about 63 percent of city's total last year,
with their exports accounting for 85.4 percent of the city's
total.
</P>
<P>
Official sources say that Fuzhou has listed 146 foreign-funded
enterprises, each with an annual production value of more than 100
million yuan, and an annual export volume of more than 10 million
dollars, in Category A.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, overseas investment has gone beyond 30 million
dollars in each of the 146 ventures in categorized in A, which
will be on the desks of the heads of the local government, to
supervise their operation.
</P>
<P>
Category B includes 151 joint ventures, each with an annual
output value of more than 30 million yuan, or a yearly export
volume of over five million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded ventures in B also include those involving in
more than 10 million dollars in overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that directors of departments of the Fuzhou City
government or the heads of suburban countries and district will
take charge of the operation of the joint ventures in the B
category.
</P>
<P>
About 166 joint ventures in Category A and B have been
put into operation, accounting for seven percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
However, the export volume of these A, B ventures reached 92
percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
The sources say that there are 23 projects in Category A and B
in construction now, which will increase the city's annual
industrial production value by 10 million yuan, when completed.
</P>
<P>
All the joint ventures not included in Category A, B will be
listed in C.  
</P>
</TEXT>
