<HEADLINE> More Trees for China's Mount Taihang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 30 percent of Mount
Taihang in north China's Hebei Province is now covered in forest,
five percent more than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, some 860,000 mu (57,333 hectares) have been planted
and seeds have been sown from aircraft on a 1.5 million mu
(100,000 hectares) area.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, eight counties and cities in the mountain
area had 4.29 million mu (286,000 hectares) of forest, including
16,000 trees planted by provincial government employees.
</P>
<P>
Mount Taihang was a revolutionary base, but was a barren area.
Now, local people from all walks of life go there to plant trees
every March 12, a national tree planting day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
