<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improves Civil Aviation Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Civil Aviation Administration
of China (CAAC) is focusing on improving the legal system in 1997,
with regulations and law enforcement playing an important role.
</P>
<P>
CAAC wants to develop 400 regulations and rules to complement
the Civil Aviation Law by the year 2000. The main task for 1997 is
the formulation of regulations on aviation safety and the aviation
market. It will pay greater attention to implementing the law and
regulations on aviation safety, market supervision, and to dealing
with passenger complaints.
</P>
<P>
CAAC will provide training programs for leading officials and
other cadres, and legal consultation for some regional
administrations and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Other measures include formulating regulations on the
responsibilities of regional administrations, requiring legal
personnel to be present at the signing of civil aviation
contracts, establishing a training and certification system for
legal consultants, and a legal counsellor system in the country's
three main airline groups.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, CAAC drafted or amended close to 40 administrative
rules and regulations on aviation safety, flight standards, air
traffic control, transport, airport management, finance,
scientific research, and education.
</P>
<P>
Legal departments were established in 37 out of 82 regional
administrations, airlines, airports and provincial administrations
by the end of last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Uganda Makes Achievements in Resuming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Cai Guozhong)
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has in recent years made
great achievements in resuming vanilla production.
</P>
<P>
Reliable statistics from a department concerned in the country
indicate that Uganda's production of vanilla dried beans had
increased from two tons in 1991 to 12 tons in 1996, representing
a five fold increase in six years and creating a new record in
the country's history.
</P>
<P>
Vanilla is a creeper-crop usually grown under coffee or banana
plantation. It is used in manufacturing spices for
food-processing and cosmetic.
</P>
<P>
Vanilla originally grows in tropical forests in eastern Mexico
and now its major producer is Madagascar which produces 70
percent of the total output of vanilla in the world.
</P>
<P>
It was in the 1940's when Asians in Uganda began to develop
vanilla plantation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Much progress was made in 1960's after Uganda's independence
in 1962. The country at that time had a record high productin of
10 tons of dried vanilla beans per year. However the production
had gone down almost to zero in the 1970's and 1980's due to the
political turmoil.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1980's when peace and stability started to
prevail across the country, a Ugandan called Sekarara trusted and
encouraged by foreign vanilla-purchasers with fund, reconstructed
a vanilla-processing factory. Furthermore, he got all kinds of
support including technical services from Uganda's central
government, because to resume vanilla production is part of
Uganda's export diversification program which is aimed at
reducing the country's dependence on coffee export for foreign
exchange earning. Coffee is still the country's number one
foreign exchange earner.
</P>
<P>
Since then he has encouraged and organised farmers to plant
vanilla and some small-scale vanilla plantations have appeared in
the districts of Mukono, Mbale, Masaka, Mpigi and Budibugyo.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the agricultural ministry, district agricultural
offices and women organisations at various levels have been
trying to provide the farmers with technical training, fertilizer
and pesticides and marketing services. Meanwhile a vanilla
farmers' association was formed to promote vanilla production,
processing and marketing.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation between Uganda and foreign countries and
international organisations also contributed to the rapid
resumption of vanilla production. A vanilla extension project was
launched in August 1992 and funded by the United States' Agency
for International Development (USAID) and the Norweigian fund for
women. The United Nations Development Programme has since the end
of the 1980's invited vanilla experts from Britain and China and
other countries to work among Uganda's vanilla growers. These
growers have much improved their skill under the experts'
guidance, thus getting bumper harvests for years.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Uganda vanilla growers held a seminar which worked
out measures to further develop vanilla production in the country
and announced a target production for the next century, that is
50 tons per year.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe that the target can be realised and Uganda
will become a new vanilla producing base in the world in the next
century, provided peace and stability are continuously to prevail
across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading S. African Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading South African newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
The Citizen
</P>
<P>
-- United Nations envoy Mohamed Sahnoun will lead the proposed
peace talks, scheduled to take place in South Africa on Saturday,
between representatives of Zairean government and rebels
controlling eastern Zaire, a UN spokesman said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Star
</P>
<P>
-- Tough measures to control water usage in South Africa,
which tighten up on the consumption of households and local
authorities, are set to become law within months in an effort to
protect a dwindling resource in an arid country.
</P>
<P>
Business Day
</P>
<P>
-- South Africa's new supply-side tax holiday scheme has so
far attracted only six applicants in the five months since it was
enacted, but the Trade and Industry Department said many more
applications are in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Sowetan
</P>
<P>
-- End-of-year holidays and the Easter period account for most
of the road deaths in the more than half a million accidents that
occurred on South African roads last year, Minister of Transport
revealed to Parliament last week. 
</P>
