<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Airline Industry Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Since 1993, the Civil Aviation
Administration of China (CAAC) no longer approves the
establishment of new air transport companies and has pushed for
mergers of small carriers with bigger ones to create large
companies and enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
Major corporate mergers include Nanjing Airlines with China
Northwest Airlines, which helped it expand in east China; Chengdu
Aircraft Maintenance Engineering Co. with China Southwest
Airlines, which improved maintenance capability; and Swan Airlines
with the Heilongjiang branch of China Northern Airlines.
</P>
<P>
China Northwest, China Southwest and China Northern are three
of the six major carriers in the country. China Southwest,
Guizhou Airlines, and Huaxia Securities Co. are working together
on Guizhou's issuing of shares.
</P>
<P>
To find funds, CAAC has helped China Eastern Airlines and China
Southern Airlines issue shares. On February 4 and 5, China Eastern
was listed on the New York and Hong Kong stock exchanges, raising
a total of 228 million US dollars, and making it the first airline
company to issue stock abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Xiamen Gaoqi International Airport Development Co. Ltd.
became the first to get a public listing on the domestic market,
with A shares being traded in Shanghai in April of 1996. That
stock issue has so far raised 2.6 billion yuan for the airline
industry.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem of inefficient management in airlines and
airports, CAAC has launched a drive to restructure businesses and
improve management and marketing methods. Some progress has been
made in this, says one official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
