<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Parliament Session Concludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The winter session of Nepal's
parliament concluded here Monday night amid an uproar as
opposition lawmakers protested against the government's failure to
present any bills during the session.
</P>
<P>
The nearly one-month session witnessed the fall of the former
coalition government under Sher Bahadur Deuba of the Nepali
Congress (NC) party, but could not pass any important bills except
a fringe one on joint housing ownership, which was presented in
the last session.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand, whose three-party
government took power three weeks ago after the Deuba government
lost a confidence vote in the lower house, told MPs that the
government has not adequate time to bring the bills to parliament.
</P>
<P>
The winter session, traditionally a bill session, was
originally expected to discuss and approve several important bills
including those on decentralization, women's property rights and
MPs' defection.
</P>
<P>
MPs of the main opposition NC party surrounded the speaker of
the lower house twice during Monday's nearly 10-hour-long meeting,
urging Prime Minister Chand to clarify his government's position
on the up-coming local elections.
</P>
<P>
Chand later told the house that the government would work
towards empowering local authorities and hold the local elections
on the schedule set by the former NC-led government.
</P>
<P>
The former government announced last month that it would
postpone the local elections, which will elect chief officers for
local administration bodies throughout the country, till mid-June
to wait for the parliamentary approval of the decentralization
bill.
</P>
<P>
Opposition MPs and local administration officers, most of them
also from the NC party, had been urging the government to hold the
elections after the passage of the bill, which is expected to give
more autonomous rights to the local bodies.
</P>
<P>
Chand, a senior leader of the National Democratic Party (RPP),
the third largest party in parliament, formed his ruling coalition
with the largest Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist
Leninist, CPN-UML) and another small party when the NC-led
government resigned following its failure to get majority support
in parliament earlier last month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
