<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Crack Down on IPR Violations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Ministry of Thailand
will seek approval from Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh to
set up a special task force to revitalize suppression of
intellectual property right (IPR) violations, it is learned today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is concerned that weak enforcement of the law on
IPR protection over the past two years could increase the risk of
Thailand facing trade retaliation from the United States and other
major trading partners.
</P>
<P>
Somporn Asavahame, deputy commerce minister, said the US Trade
Representative appeared to be unhappy with the IPR situation in
Thailand and that this may lead to a decision to retain Thailand
on the regular watchlist, or even put it on the priority
watchlist, subject to more serious retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Sean Murphy, director of the Asia Pacific Office of the US
Trade Representative (USTR), visited Thailand earlier this month
to monitor the latest developments in the country's IPR
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
The US official implied that the Thai government has yet to
follow up on its commitment to pass the patent act and step up
enforcement of copyright violations.
</P>
<P>
The USTR reviews annually the status of trading patterns in
April and announces its decision in October.
</P>
<P>
The US government moved Thailand from its serious watchlist to
regular watchlist in November 1994 and restored generalized system
of preferences (GSP) benefits on 15 Thai export items in July 1995
after the Thai government promised to reduce the number of
violations.
</P>
<P>
Some Thai officials fear that the overwhelming volume of
copyright violations in Bangkok might prompt the USTR to leave
Thailand on its watchlist during the upcoming revision.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
