<HEADLINE> Southeast Asian Nuke Ban Takes Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The treaty banning nuclear weapons
in Southeast Asia has taken effect, the Thai Foreign Ministry
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Foreign Ministry Acting Spokesman Thinakorn Kanasuta said
that the Southeast Asia Nuclear Weapon-Free Zone Treaty, signed by
10 nations in the region in December 1995, came into effect last
Thursday after Cambodia and Singapore recently approved it.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar, Laos, Malaysia, Vietnam, Brunei and Thailand earlier
had approved the pact, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was first signed by heads of government from
Myanmar, Cambodia, Laos and the seven members of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in December 1995 during the
fifth ASEAN summit in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The treaty bans the signatories from developing, producing,
possessing and acquiring nuclear weapons in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
