<HEADLINE> China's Largest Speciality Market Opens in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai East China Trading
Plaza, believed to be China's largest speciality marketplace,
opened here last week.
</P>
<P>
Covering one square kilometer, the plaza cost over two billion
yuan (240 million US dollars) in investment and was paid for by
both mainland and Hongkong partners.
</P>
<P>
It has six markets dealing in clothing and textiles, decorative
materials, bedding, and foodstuff and small commodities, and 12
more markets that are expected to be added within five years.
</P>
<P>
A "Chinese Brandname Products Street" will also be built in the
plaza by the China Trademark Association. All space places
available during the first phase of construction has been booked.
</P>
<P>
It will provide dealers with essential services like water,
electricity, and telecommunications, as well educational
services for children. It will be connected to the Internet to
provide market information. 
</P>
