<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Offers Open Discussion With Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina Monday offered dialogue with opposition leader Khaleda Zia
to settle the most important or contentious national issues in a
bid to defuse political tension.
</P>
<P>
Hasina said she is ready for talks with the leader of the
opposition or sit for a live debate or discussion on TV for
thrashing out the issues, including the confrontational situation
between the government and the opposition.
</P>
<P>
"We have several times invited the opposition leader to sit for
open debate to explain to the people what we are doing and what
they," she told a group of editors Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist
Party Chairperson Khaleda Zia gave a seven-day ultimatum to the
government to arrest the killers of two of her party workers in
Feni city, 136 kilometers southeast of capital Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
"Otherwise we will announce tough agitation programs separately
for the Chittagong division," she told a large public meeting in
Feni town, adding that Sheikh Hasina, after coming to power, has
unleashed a reign of terror on the opposition party workers.
</P>
<P>
Hasina, who defeated former prime minister Khaleda Zia in
election last June, told the editors that her government
repeatedly invited the opposition to cooperate with the government
in development activities to ensure rapid and smooth development
of the country.
</P>
<P>
However, at a time when the government is continuing its
all-out efforts to improve the situation of the country to rebuild
the national image, the opposition party is calling for strike,
and acts of sabotage are going on to disturb the calm in the
country, she alleged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
