<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Chief Optimistic About Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary Renato
de Villa has expressed satisfaction over the forming of a joint
committee to oversee a local ceasefire in Buldon, the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by today's local press as saying that the
creation of the committee was a "very significant" and
"encouraging" development in the peace negotiations between the
government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF), a
12,000-member rebel group in the country.
</P>
<P>
De Villa said he was pleased that the MILF accepted the
military's suggestion that four non-government organizations be
tapped to become members of the joint monitoring committee.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the government peace panel had held two
preliminary talks with the two sides agreeing to form the said
joint committee to ensure the implementation of the local
ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
However, the talks are sometimes stalled due to sporadic
fighting between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the MILF and the military exchanged accusations on
who was responsible for the death of 10 students and a teacher in
an exchange of mortar fire in Buldon.
</P>
<P>
A few days later, another clash occurred, wounding at least
three soldiers in the same area.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a splinter group of the Moro National Liberation
Front which ended its armed struggle against the government last
year, is expected to hold the third round of talks with the
government this month to set a timetable for their future formal
peace talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
