<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Eighth Amendment to Be Revised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistan Muslim League
(PML-N) led by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has decided to do away
with some portions of the most controversial and much abused
Eighth Amendment in order to restore supremacy of parliament.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Nawaz Sharif in his televised
address to the nation last night.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that President Farooq Leghari had
happily agreed to the PML(N)'s historic decision during his
meeting with him Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sharif was thankful to Leghari for giving his consent and said
a complex constitutional issue has been solved amicably and
through mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
With the annulment of some of its portions, the prime minister
said, the Eighth Amendment will go away with all its bitter parts
and memories.
</P>
<P>
The infamous amendment was inserted in the constitution in 1985
by the party-less parliament when the late General Zia ul-Haq was
the chief martial law administrator and president of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Its most notorious provision, 58(2)(B), has since been used for
four times to dismiss elected governments and has been a source of
constant political instability.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendment, the president has discretionary powers to
dismiss the government and the national assembly, appoint services
chiefs and the chairman of the joint chiefs of staff committee and
chief election commissioner.
</P>
<P>
Nawaz Sharif said the decision to scrap some portions of the
amendment was taken to revive the democratic concept as envisaged
by the founder of the nation, greater leader Quaid-e-Azam.
</P>
<P>
The decision to dispense with these portions followed lengthy
and serious discussions among the PML parliamentary and its allied
parties, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Increases International Police Presence in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
today authorized a major strengthening of the U.N. International
Police Task Force (IPTF) in Bosnia's disputed northern town of
Brcko.
</P>
<P>
A total of 186 police and 11 civilian personnel will join the
30 international police already stationed in Serb-held Brcko,
which is claimed by both Bosnian Serbs and the Bosnian-Croat
Federation.
</P>
<P>
Brcko has been placed under international supervision pending a
final solution on the town's status in March next year.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council unanimously passed the resolution to send
the forces and stressed the importance of ensuring that the IPTF
is able to carry out the tasks outlined in the Dayton Peace
Agreement which ended the near four-year war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The IPTF is to monitor, observe and inspect policing activities
and facilities, advise and train police personnel and forces, help
law enforcement activities and and assess threats to public order.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council's decision comes following U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's request on March 18 for an
extra 306 international police in Bosnia, including the 186
for Brcko.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council urged member states to provide qualified
police monitors and other forms of assistance to support the
IPTF.
</P>
<P>
It also called upon all parties in the Dayton Peace Agreement,
signed in December 1995, to implement all aspects of the agreement
to cooperate with IPTF in the conduct of its activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civilians Cooperate With Sri Lankan Forces Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan government troops on
Sunday recovered a large haul of bombs and grenades during a
search operation in Jaffna peninsula following information
provided by Tamil civilians, according to military sources here
today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Tamil civilians who have moved into army-
occupied territory in northern Sri Lanka are cooperating with the
armed forces against the rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE).
</P>
<P>
The civilians have informed the forces as to where large stocks
of rebel arms and ammunition were hidden and the forces were able
to unearth them in the past several months, the sources noted.
</P>
<P>
More civilians who were living in the LTTE-controlled areas
have of late moved into the security forces-controlled areas in
Northern province and were supplying information to the forces
about Tiger hideouts.
</P>
<P>
Consequently the forces have been able to flush out rebels and
arrest them at various places in the north, particularly in Jaffna
peninsula, they added.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been waging a 14-year war against the Sri Lankan
government for a separate state in the north and east of the
country. During this period over 55,000 persons are reported to
have been killed.
</P>
<P>
Efforts by the present government for a dialogue to end the war
was reneged by the rebels. And consequently the government has
launched major offensives against the rebels and dislodged them
from their heartland, Jaffna peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Now the LTTE rebels have taken refuge in nearby jungles while
government forces have controlled Jaffna peninsula and its
surroundings since last May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
