<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Bad-loan Crisis Hits East Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- There are two sides to everything,
and Asia's economic miracle is no exception. If the steady and
high growth could be described as the bright side of the miracle,
then, the bad-loan crisis is its dark side.
</P>
<P>
Five years ago, when Japan started experiencing the bad-loan
crisis, no one expected that years later, the crisis would spread
to other parts of Asia, the region with fastest economic growth in
the world for the last decade.
</P>
<P>
Now, from Tokyo to Seoul, from Bangkok to Jakarta, lenders have
run up about 660 billion U.S. dollars in non-performing loans to
over-extended real estate developers, money-losing state
enterprises, and politically connected corporate deadbeats.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, Ssangyong group, the country's sixth biggest
conglomerate, is reportedly looking for foreign buyers for half
its carmaking unit, Ssangyong Motor, which has more than 3 billion
dollars in debt.
</P>
<P>
But Ssangyong's case is not an isolated one in South Korea.
Many companies there are suffering from the same disease -- high
debt-to-equity ratios caused by borrowing too much, too quickly to
finance growth. Most companies' debt is nearly three times their
equity, and for some outfits it is more than 10 times.
</P>
<P>
Within three months, two major conglomerates have collapsed in
the country: the Hanbo group in January and the Sammi group in
March. The Hanbo group, South Korea's 14th-biggest conglomerate
and its number two steel maker, had 5.8 billion dollars in debt,
while the Sammi group, the nation's 26th biggest conglomerate,
cracked under debts of 2.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In Thailand, years of go-go development left lenders with
non-performing credits that represent roughly 10 percent, or 15.5
billion dollars, of their loan portfolios. The debt has amounted
to nearly 9 percent of Thailand's gross domestic product (GDP) and
is expected to expand in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, a World Bank study says, nearly 17 percent of
state-owned banks' loans are non-performing, or shaky.
</P>
<P>
However, by comparison, things in Japan are still the worst.
Japanese banks are in the fifth year of a battle with a stagnant
economy. Collapsing equity and property prices have left them with
at least 350 billion dollars in bad loans.
</P>
<P>
Economists blamed mis-management for the spreading of the
bad-loan crisis in the region. From Japan to Thailand, they said,
many banks lack credit and cost controls and as a result, banks
have lent too much money to property developers, money-losing
enterprises and politically connected companies.
</P>
<P>
With a wary eye on bad-debt problems in its neighboring
countries, Malaysia's central bank has moved to curb lending to
property and stock purchasers. Starting today, Malaysian banks can
lend only up to 20 percent of total loans for property projects
"deemed less productive." Commercial banks and finance companies
will not be able to lend out more than 15 percent of total loans
for customers to invest in stocks and mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
As the crisis is so serious, fixing this mess would take years
and cost hundreds of billions of dollars, if not more, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
They said that if the current problems are allowed to fester,
Asian banks could be trapped with bad loans weakening their
capital bases. That would severely crimp their ability to make new
loans.
</P>
<P>
The bad-loan crisis has a grave impact on the economic growth
in the region. As a response to the crisis, banks in some
countries have tightened credit and slowed growth in government
spending. These moves would push some of the world's most dynamic
countries into the sort of economic slump.
</P>
<P>
In South Korea, the troubles have sent many experts scurrying
to readjust their forecast for the nation's economy. Compared to
the government's initial GDP growth projection of 6 percent for
this year, the Samsung Economic Research Institute now predicts an
increase of just 5 percent. At such a rate, the nation's
unemployment is bound to increase from the present 2.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a solution to the crisis, experts suggested that Asian banks
change their corporate culture and put risk control and
profitability ahead of rank expansionism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0215 </DOCNO>
