<HEADLINE> Georgian President Urges Support for Extended Abkhazia Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Edward
Shevardnadze Monday called for support for a decision by the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) on extending the mission
of its peace-keeping force in the break-away Abkhazia Republic.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax agency quoted Shevardnadze as saying in a routine
weekend radio speech that the implementation of the CIS resolution
involved the comprehensive settlement of the Abkhazian conflict.
The conflict began in August 1992, after the republic declared
independence from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The CIS member states agreed at a summit meeting Friday to
extend the mandate of the CIS peace-keeping force in Abkhazia to
July 31, as requested by Shevardnadze.
</P>
<P>
The mandate of the 2,500-member CIS peace-keeping force,
deployed in June 1994 to help monitor a ceasefire that ended the
war, had already been extended once to April 1996 at a CIS summit
in January last year.
</P>
<P>
The CIS decision met opposition from Abkhazian Parliament
Speaker Sokrat Djindjoliya, who said the resolution did not take
into account the opinions of Abkhazia, and was a unilateral action.
</P>
<P>
The speaker vowed that Abkhazia would not allow the CIS
peace-keeping force to expand its security zone in Abkhazia, as
proposed by Shevardnadze.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last month, the United Nations Security Council also
decided to extend the U.N. observers' mission in Georgia to July
31 this year.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people were killed in the Georgian-Abkhazian
conflict. It was prompted by the Georgian government's dispatch of
troops to the seceding region located on the Black Sea, in
northwestern Georgia,
</P>
<P>
Talks between the Georgian government and the Abkhazian
authorities have stalled and resumed from time to time as the two
sides disagree over key issues including the status of Abkhazia
and the repatriation of tens of thousands of refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
