<HEADLINE> Soft Interior Decoration Becoming Popular in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- More and more urban dwellers in
China are turning to textiles to soften the look of their home, as
Chinese taste in interior design shifts from the practical to the
aesthetic.
</P>
<P>
Well-off urban residents in the past decorated their homes with
wood, ceramic tiles or mosaics, but many now prefer exquisite
curtains and unique tapestries, especially newly-married couples
and newly-moved-in families.
</P>
<P>
Flourishing firms which specialize in selling curtains and
textiles strongly support the change. Softer decor is finding more
favor in the eyes of consumers, as it costs less and can be easily
created to satisfy individual taste, experts say.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 firms in Changchun, the capital of northeast
China's Jilin Province, are all making considerable profits by
selling colorful curtains and textiles for interior decoration.
</P>
<P>
The new look was initiated in south China and has gradually
spread to the north and west, one firm manager says, and is now
accepted by most urban citizens.
</P>
<P>
Rapid development of high-grade hotels and the service
industry as well as improved office environments, will further
promote the softer styles, the manager predicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
