<HEADLINE> China Raises Trains' Speed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Even though the ticket price is
still the same, China's trains are running faster as of today, in
a move to beat competition from buses and airliners.
</P>
<P>
Trains on three major lines - the Beijing-Guangzhou,
Beijing-Shanghai, and Beijing-Harbin - will have a maximum speed
of 140 kilometers per hour, while trains on other railway lines
will have a speed of 120 km per hour, the Ministry of Railways
says.
</P>
<P>
This will increase the average speed of the country's trains
from the current 48.1 to 54.9 km ph, and the maximum speed of
long-distance passenger trains, 97.6 km per hour.
</P>
<P>
In order to win back travelers, many of whom in recent years
have changed to buses and airlines for speed and comfort, the
Ministry of Railways will start 78 "arrive-in-a-night" trains from
large and medium-sized cities, including Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou, Chengdu, and Zhengzhou, for destinations within a
1,500-km range.
</P>
<P>
Highway and civil aviation industries have been developing
rapidly in China, while rail transport has seen a steady decrease
in the past few years. Statistics show trains carried only 942
million passengers last year, a 12.3 percent drop from the
previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
