<HEADLINE> Leading Chinese Ham Producer Aims High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Chundu Conglomerate of
Luoyang City, in central China's Henan Province, is hoping to
build itself into an important food company on the world market by
using overseas funds and importing the world's most advanced
technology.
</P>
<P>
Gao Fenglai, the company's general manager, says that it is
paying close attention to market changes and now dominates China's
ham market. The central Chinese province now has 17 factories
capable of producing 300,000 tons of ham annually, accounting for
90 percent of the country's total ham output.
</P>
<P>
Gao's conglomerate contributes 200,000 tons to the province's
total, and has 2.4 billion yuan in sales each year and 150 million
yuan in net profits.
</P>
<P>
This contrasts sharply with ten years ago, when the company was
a state-owned meat processing factory on the verge of being shut
down because of fierce competition.
</P>
<P>
In 1986, the factory spent a million yuan on a ham-production
machine at an international food machinery fair in Zhengzhou,
Henan's capital, marking the start of a new business.
</P>
<P>
After an extensive study of the domestic market and China's
consumer conditions, the factory began producing "Chundu" brand
hams, which have a shelf life of three months. "Chundu" is now a
household word in China, as product quality was improved and
diversified in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Chundu set up the joint-stock Sino-foreign Chundu
Group Company with 300 million yuan raised from overseas
investment organizations, with Chundu Conglomerate holding the
majority. It is now planning to establish a financial company for
borrowing and lending, to help it expand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
