<HEADLINE> Displaced Miners in Shanxi Province Find New Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 130,000 laid-off miners
are doing just as well in non-mining industries in China's major
coal producer, Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The newly-launched non-mining industries are capable of
producing more than three billion yuan-worth of annual output
value, and are expected to match the mining industry by the end of
the century.
</P>
<P>
Coal mining is the province's pillar industry, but poor
performance and over-staffing have hindered its development. One
third of the coal industry's output value was eaten up by wages
and salaries.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide restructuring of state-owned enterprises and the
introduction of a modern enterprise system have promoted
mechanization and upgrading of Shanxi's coal mines, which left
some 130,000 of the province's total 400,000 coal miners jobless.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the province's key coal mines have raised 268.76
million yuan to create new job opportunities for the surplus labor
force. To date, 64 projects centering on the service sector have
been completed, supported by low-interest government loans
totaling 416.9 million yuan and overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
The non-mining industry has risen at an average rate of 30
percent in terms of annual output value over the past two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
