<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laid-off Worker Says Finding A Job Not So Difficult in Shenyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Most workers who lost their jobs
at ailing state-owned enterprises in Shenyang, capital of
northeast China's Liaoning Province, have gone to the city's
booming commercial and service industries to look for jobs.
</P>
<P>
Local officials say that most of the city's 300,000 laid-off
workers have found places in the commercial and service sector,
either by opening a small business of their own, or by working for
privately-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Chen, one of the city's large number of jobless, became a
taxi driver after he was given a long holiday by his company two
years ago. But, he said, "My misfortune has turned out to be a
blessing now, and I earn much more than what I used to in the
state-owned enterprise."
</P>
<P>
"It's not too difficult for us to find jobs again," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The city's largest labor market, a part-time job service center
in the Heping District, has become a place frequently visited by
local laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that local laid-off workers have taken up about a
third of the jobs available in a market that was previously
dominated by farmers flooding the city looking for work.
</P>
<P>
Laid-off workers are better educated than farmers and more
competitive at finding work, the sources say, and some workers
have become bosses of their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
The city has some 300,000 people involved in privately-run
businesses, and the figure is growing at an annual rate of more
than 20 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
