<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Develop More New Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China will subsidize research on
new drugs effective on brain vascular illnesses, tumors and
virulent diseases in the next three years, reported today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
At least ten such new drugs will be developed in China by 2000,
with one or two marketed in developed countries, said Wang
Mingxue, an official with the State Pharmaceutical Administration
(SPA).
</P>
<P>
By achieving these goals, Wang said, the country will gradually
divert the pharmaceutical industry from drug imitation to
innovation, setting up a practicable drug research and development
system.
</P>
<P>
The SPA encourages scientists to research on potential Chinese
patent drugs to compete with foreign products, he said.
</P>
<P>
The SPA and the State Science and Technology Commission are
building up five new medicine safety evaluation centers and five
new clinical research centers in line with international
standards, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country is capable of producing 1,350
varieties of bulk pharmaceuticals, more than 3,500 kinds of
pharmaceutical preparations and 4,000 varieties of traditional
Chinese medicines.
</P>
<P>
About half of the medicines produced in China have been raised
to the level of developed countries.
</P>
<P>
More than ten percent of prescribed medicines have been
prepared in line with international requirements for Good
Manufacture Practice.
</P>
<P>
To expedite research and development of new drugs, a National
Co-ordination Committee of New Drug Research was set up in 1993
composed of officials from 11 commissions, ministries and
administrations including the State Science and Technology
Commission, SPA and the Ministry of Public Health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
