<HEADLINE> King Hussein Feels Hopeful on Middle East Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Hussein is
hopeful that there is a basis for moving forward the Middle East
peace process, United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
here today.
</P>
<P>
"He felt we could get over this bump and move the process
forward," Annan said after discussions with King Hussein, who
spent several hours with Annan at his residence today.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian talks have been disrupted since Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu broke ground for new Jewish
settlements in Arab East Jerusalem two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
After seeing King Hussein, Annan met with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright. Albright said that the peace process was
in a difficult phase. She appealed to all sides to avoid any
initiatives that would jeopardize the process further.
</P>
<P>
At a dinner honoring King Hussein today, Albright called on
Arabs and Israelis to give up "old thinking and old habits" in
order to forge a Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
"The process of creating confidence, forging agreements and
meeting commitments can be painstaking and painful," she said. "It
requires a steadfast adherence to principle and steadfast
opposition to terror."
</P>
<P>
She praised King Hussein's move of making peace with Israel in
1994, which had taught others that reconciliation among peoples
begins at the individual level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
