<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Approves 400-Million-Dollar Reorganization Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank board approved
today a reorganization plan of 400 million U.S. dollars designed
to make the bank more effective in fighting poverty around the
world.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the plan is to enable the bank to act
more rapidly and improve its results because private capital flows
to developing countries have dwarfed official aid from the bank
and other institutions.
</P>
<P>
World Bank President James D. Wolfensohn said that the bank had
to put greater emphasis on helping poor countries build up their
institutions and infrastructure so they would become more
attractive to private capital.
</P>
<P>
On the reorganization plan itself, he said the bank would
finance the plan so none of its 180 members "would have to
write checks" to pay for the plan.
</P>
<P>
He also told the board's 24 governors there will be no
golden-parachute payoffs for employees near retirement who are
losing the jobs as part of the reorganization.
</P>
<P>
The plan calls for an additional 150 million dollars to be
spent on termination payments.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said the board approved an initial 60 million
dollars for dismissal indemnities and wants to closely monitor how
Wolfensohn and his managers go about the terminations, put at up
to 700 people in the initial plan.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said he and his managers were ready to be dismissed
if the board at its twice yearly review of the reorganization
decided he was not getting the job done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
