<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Peacekeepers' Stay in Angola Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council decided unanimously today to extend the stay of
the 6,240-member U.N. peacekeeping force in war-torn Angola until
April 16, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Council also decided to consider applying sanction measures
against a party that tried to delay the establishment of a new
coalition government in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Council took the move at the suggestion of U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan who said in his latest report that
over the past six weeks little progress had been made towards the
establishment of a Government of Unity and National Reconciliation
in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Annan attributed the failure to Angola's major anti-government
force, Uniao Nacional para a Independencia Total de Angola
(UNITA), which did not send to Luanda its officials who had been
designated to join the Angola National Assembly and the new
government.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the Security Council intended to
pressure UNITA to join the Angola new government, so that the
remaining part of the Lusaka Protocol could be fulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Angola has suffered civil war between the ruling People's
Movement for the Liberation of Angola (PMLA) and the opposition
UNITA since 1976 when Portuguese colonial rule ended.
</P>
<P>
Under the mediation of the U.N., the United States, Russia and
Portugal, the Angola government and UNITA signed a peace protocol
in the Zambian capital of Lusaka in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The protocol called for a ceasefire, deployment of
U.N. peacekeeping troops to monitor the ceasefire, dismissal of
UNITA forces, UNITA officials to join the central and the local
governments, and the holding of a new presidential election at a
time acceptable to both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
