<HEADLINE> Myanmar's GDP Up 5.8 Percent in 1996-97 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's Gross Domestic Product
(GDP) registered a 5.8 percent increase in the 1996-97 fiscal year
which ended on March 31, according to an official report today.
</P>
<P>
The productive sector increased by 6.2 percent, services sector
by 6.3 percent and trade sector by 5.8 percent respectively
compared with the previous year, it said.
</P>
<P>
The 1996-97 fiscal year was the first year of Myanmar's current
five-year plan (1996-97 to 2000-2001), the average annual growth
target of which was set at 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The last four-year plan (1992-93 to 1995-96) saw an average
annual growth rate of 7.3 percent compared with the original
target of 5.6 percent, mainly due to the growth achieved by the
agriculture sector, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Major plan targets for 1997-98 fiscal year, which begins today,
are set at 6.4 percent increase in GDP, in which agriculture to
increase by 6.3 per cent, said the report, adding that total value
of exports is projected to increase from 5.2 to 5.9 billion Kyats
(about 866 to 983 million U.S. dollars according to official
exchange rate) and that of imports to increase from 10.8 to 11.2
billion Kyats (about 1.8 to 1.87 billion U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
