<HEADLINE> Taiwan Acrobatic Master to Drive across Yellow River Waterfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Renowned Taiwan acrobatic master Ke
Shouliang, who successfully drove a car down the Great Wall in
1992, plans to drive a car across the Hukou Waterfall on China's
Yellow River on June 1.
</P>
<P>
The more than 60-meter-wide waterfall lies on the border
between north China's Shanxi and Shaanxi provinces, with water
falling 30-plus meters to the ground.
</P>
<P>
On June 1, the 44-year-old Taiwan master, known as "the first
skyman of Asia," plans to begin driving on the Shanxi side, go
airborne over the water, and land on the Shaanxi side.
</P>
<P>
"I hope my driving adventure on the Yellow River will serve to
inspire Chinese nationals the world over to care more about and
try their best for their motherland's progress," Ke said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Ke's driving stunt, the event -- part of the
"Visit China '97" campaign -- will feature other acts of daring
involving cars and helicopters, as well as musical numbers and
choirs. The two-hour display will be attended by actors and
actresses from Hong Kong, Taiwan and the inland, as well as an
audience of some 50,000.
</P>
<P>
Crossing the river will be very difficult, as the distance
between the starting point and the water's edge is only 200
meters, said Zhang Xiaoke, deputy director of the Shaanxi
Provincial Tourism Administration.
</P>
<P>
But he claimed that Ke's daring stunt will add extra "colorful
flavor" to the day.
</P>
<P>
Before his June 1 driving adventure, Ke will donate money to
set up two "Hope" primary schools on both sides of the Hukou
Waterfall, one in Jixian County of Shanxi and one in Yichuan
County of Shaanxi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
