<HEADLINE> Venezuela Attracts More Foreign Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign capital directly invested
in Venezuela in 1996 increased by 27 percent over the previous
year, the Superintendency of Foreign Investments (SIEX) said today.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of foreign investments in 1996 was about 7.5
billion U.S. dollars, the SIEX said today.
</P>
<P>
The petroleum sector received the biggest volume of capital,
followed by such sectors as commerce, agriculture and livestock
breeding, construction, transportation and electrical and water
services.
</P>
<P>
The United States was usually the principal source of foreign
investment but last year it was outranked by Holland.
</P>
<P>
Regional capital accounted for 11 percent of all foreign
investments in Venezuela. Inflows of Latin American capital have
increased since 1991 following the economic opening up of the
countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The SIEX attributed the increase of foreign investments to
regional integration, privatization and favorable legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
