<HEADLINE> Argentine Defense Minister Meets Chinese Military Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Argentine Defense Minister
Jorge Dominguez today held talks on bilateral relations with a
Chinese military delegation headed by Zhang Wannian, vice chairman
of the Central Military Commission of China.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, both sides emphasized the importance of
pursuing a foreign policy of independence, self-determination and
non-interference in the internal affairs of other countries. They
also expressed satisfaction over the cooperative and friendly
relations between the two countries and armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Dominguez said that his government has attached great
importance to the development of the friendly relations with China
and will continue to make its efforts to promote bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
He added that both Argentina and China have participated in
U.N. peacekeeping operations and can exchange experience in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
Dominguez expressed his condolences over the death of Chinese
leader Deng Xiaoping, saying Deng was a world leader.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Zhang said that China's defense policy is of a
defensive nature. China's armed forces do not seek to interfere in
other countries' internal affairs, to form military alliance with
other countries, to send troops to other countries and to
establish military bases abroad.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that China's foreign policy is oriented to peace
and development.
</P>
<P>
Zhang also met with Argentine President Carlos Menem this
morning. He will hold separate meetings tomorrow with other top
military officials to exchange experience and enhance mutual
understanding.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese military delegation arrived here yesterday for a
four-day visit to this South American country. It will leave
Argentina on April 4 to continue its South America tour which will
also take it to Chile and Brazil. 
</P>
