<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Ranks Fifth in Internet Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand boasts the fifth
highest number of Internet-linked computers, known as hosts, per
head of population among the world countries.
</P>
<P>
The local magazine NZ Infotech Weekly today quoted a global
survey conducted by the California-based consultancy Network
Wizards in January that New Zealand's placing is below Finland,
Norway, the United States and Australia, but ahead of Britain,
France and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that hosts in New Zealand totaled over 84,000
in January, up 58 percent from the numbers a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
But many hosts are used by more than one person, so the actual
number of New Zealanders using the Internet is likely to be very
much greater than the figure suggests, according to the survey.
</P>
</TEXT>
