<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPPCC, Non-Communist Parties Help Poor Farmers in Guizhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- More than one million farmers in
southwest China's Guizhou Province have shaken off poverty thanks
to an anti-poverty technical program.
</P>
<P>
The program is initiated by local committees of the Chinese
people's political consultative conference (CPPCC), non-Communist
parties, and the federations of industry and commerce.
</P>
<P>
Farmers in Jiaoyao village of Leishan County were the first to
benefit from the program. In the early 1980s, they lived in
thatched sheds, fed on relief grains provided by the state, and
had no more than 28 yuan of annual income per capita. But now
every family has a new house with running water, and their per
capita annual income is 2,053 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Experts and technicians from the committee of CPPCC of the Miao
and Dong Nationalities Autonomous Prefecture came to the village
in 1980 with new rice strains and new farming techniques.
</P>
<P>
As a result, rice output rose to 6,000 kilograms from 2,200
kilograms per hectare as a result, according to Wang Siming,
vice-chairman of the CPPCC Provincial Committee.
</P>
<P>
Farmers came to know the good of science, as their farm work
relies heavily on it. They even built a new school after raising
30,000 yuan, hoping that their children will become better
educated.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the Revolutionary Committee of the
Chinese Kuomintang invited Zhang Wenbing, a fruit tree expert, to
help cultivate high-yield fruit trees in Nayong County, and Zhang
has been in the county four times for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
More than 36,000 personnel are involved in the technical
poverty alleviation campaign, covering 200-plus townships and
villages. And 8,560 projects have been completed with 1.5 million
farmers trained and 40 vocational-technical schools set up,
Wang said. enditem

nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
