<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- China yesterday released a white paper on the progress in
its human rights cause in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The white paper, entitled "Progress in China's Human Rights
Cause in 1996," and released by the Information Office of the State
Council, is a comprehensive reflection of the progress that China
has scored in its human rights cause in the past year.
</P>
<P>
The 13,000-character white paper includes seven parts: One:
People's Rights to Subsistence and Development; Two: Citizens'
Democratic Rights; Three: Judicial Guarantee for Human Rights;
Four: Protection of Workers' Rights; Five: Citizens' Rights to
Receive Education; Six: Legitimate Rights and Interests of Women
and Children; Seven: Guarantee of Rights of Ethnic Minorities.
</P>
<P>
-- The Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and the
State Council have jointly issued a 13-point joint decision
ordering all localities and departments to reduce burdens on
farmers by canceling all kinds of illegal levies.
</P>
<P>
While the economic situation in the rural areas is enjoying
overall development, the document says, in some places farmers are
still weighed down by rampant unlawful charges by local
departments.
</P>
<P>
The decision prohibits any means to be used to collect cash and
goods from farmers, who have the right to turn down illegal
charges and to take their cases to the court.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng told visiting Australian Prime
Minister John Howard Monday that China and Australia, both
influential countries in the Asia-Pacific region, should join
hands in pushing forward the development of bilateral relations of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Li hoped that Howard's current visit will further existing
friendship between China and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Howard emphasized that China is a very important cooperative
partner of Australia, and China's enormous economic progress
offers extremely favorable cooperative opportunities for his
country.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng Monday urged the country's young
scientists to open their minds and be adventurous in their
research in order to make greater contributions to the development
of science and technology and the country's modernization.
</P>
<P>
Li made the request during a meeting with a group of Chinese
scientists, all under 45, from the Chinese Academy of
Sciences. The group gathered in Beijing to discuss the necessity
of nurturing young scientists and to explore ways to perfect
policies in this respect.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China has pledged to further improve the living, studying
and labor reform environment of prisoners by 2000, said an
official from the Ministry of Justices.
</P>
<P>
It is anticipated that many Chinese prisoners will be equipped
with modern facilities and prison management will be improved to
prevent recidivism, said Zhang Xiufu, executive vice-minister of
Justice at a press conference held yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- Two Chinese vessels will soon embark for the northeastern
Pacific Ocean to prospect for natural resources. The exploratory
mission is intended to find strategic resource reserves for China
in the next century.
</P>
<P>
The mission will also be responsible for surveying the
distribution of mineral resources and the mining environment
5,000 meters deep, while making preparations for developing marine
resources for commercial exploitation on a large-scale in the next
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
