<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Forest Park Built in Revolutionary Mecca </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A national forest park is taking
shape in Yan'an, a revolutionary base of the Communist Party of
China in northwest China in the 1930s and 1940s.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are already 3,600 ha of forests in and around
the city in Shaanxi Province, bringing its afforestation rate up
to 66.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The afforestation fever in the city dates back to 1956, when
the Central Committee of the Communist Youth League of China held
a conference in the city calling for the youth in northwest
regions to add green areas to their homes.
</P>
<P>
Now, a forest belt 12 km long and ten km wide has taken shape
around the city.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the Ministry of Forestry approved for Yan'an the
establishment of a national forest park, consisting of 1,332 ha of
trees specially for tourism and 60 ha of forests for economic
purposes.
</P>
<P>
So far, 26.7 ha of trees have been planted annually in the
park. The afforestation rate in the park is expected to rise to
80.29 percent when the park is completed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nanning Cracks Down on Illegal Sale of Wild Animals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A joint law-enforcement team in
Nanning has launched a large-scale operation to crack down on the
illegal sales of wild animals under protection of both the state
and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The team, headed by officials from the Regional Industry and
Commerce Administration, ferreted out the illegal sale of 29
wild animals in restaurants and a free market in Jinan Street from
March 5 to 20.
</P>
<P>
The animals retrieved by the officers include masket civets,
owls, cobras and bamboo rats.
</P>
<P>
The team consists of 40 officials from the bureaus of
agriculture, forestry, environmental protection and public
security, and the Regional Industry and Commerce Administration.
</P>
<P>
The group handed over all the seized wild animals and the fined
money to the wild animal protection stations under the forestry
bureau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
