<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspected Arson Kills Three Turks in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 31 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish woman and two of her
children were killed with two others serious injured in a fire
broke out today in their apartment building in the western German
town of Krefeld, arson being suspected, said reports reaching
here.
</P>
<P>
Local police investigating the case said lighter fluid had been
poured and ignited in the third-floor hallway outside the Turkish
family's flat in the 13-storey apartment building.
</P>
<P>
Fellow occupants and police who happened to be in the area when
the fire broke out tried to convince the Turkish family to stay
calm and wait for help.
</P>
<P>
But with fire blocking all the escape routes, the
panic-stricken 41-year-old Turkish woman threw a mattress onto the
ground some 12 meters below and jumped out of the window, followed
by her three daughters -- a 19-year-old and her 15-year-old twin
sisters.
</P>
<P>
The 41-year-old died instantly from the jump while her
19-year-old daughter died later in hospital. The twins were
critically injured. The woman's 17-year-old son remained in the
flat and died of smoke inhalation, police said.
</P>
<P>
Although police suspected arson, officials said there were no
immediate evidents pointing to a xenophobic attack.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish community in Germany called for a swift
clarification of the incident while Turkish ambassador in Bonn
Volkan Vural said in an interview with a local television after
the incident that xenophobia and racist attacks are "reality in
Germany."
</P>
<P>
About 500 Krefeld residents gathered before the apartment
building this evening in protest against the attack while another
group of people demonstrated on the streets, chanting, "Turkey,
Turkey," the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
