<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Tumble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 31 (Xinhua) -- Stocks tumbled again on Wall
Street today, giving the Dow Jones industrial average a two-day
loss of nearly 300 points, as interest rate worries continued to
eat away at the robust gains of the past half year.
</P>
<P>
The Dow lost 157.11 points, its sixth worst point-drop in
history, closing at 6,583.48, plunging below 6,600 for the first
time since early January and trimming the year's gain to only
slightly more than 2 percent. Just three weeks ago, when it set an
all-time high at 7,085.16 on March 11, the Dow was up nearly 10
percent on the year.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly a 4-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume jumping to
555.73 million shares from 475.93 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Other key stock measures also extended Thursday's selloff,
which was spurred by growing fears the Federal Reserve will keep
raising interest rates to fight against inflation. The stock
market was closed on Good Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 list, a popular model for many mutual
funds, and the technology-laden Nasdaq composite index both fell
more than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The S&AMP;P 500 fell 16.76 to 757.12, and the NYSE composite index
fell 8.88 to 398.55.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite fell 27.81 to 1,221.70, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index fell 9.19 to 368.71. The Russell
2000 list of smaller companies fell 6.39 to 342.56.
</P>
<P>
Stocks started the session sharply lower despite a firm bond
market, where prices initially edged higher and the yield on the
30-year Treasury bond dipped below 7.07 percent.
</P>
<P>
The fears of higher rates at the Fed and the bond market
produced more selling in the banking and financial services
sector, where profits shrink as lending costs rise. The Dow's
biggest decliners included J.P. Morgan, Travelers Group, and
American Express. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
