<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Mulls Over Mideast Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton today
discussed the tense situation in the Middle East with his peace
broker Dennis Ross on the eve of a visit by King Hussein of
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry, in a briefing to reporters
about the meeting, said the United States continued to encourage
the Israelis and Palestinians to "recognize the utility of
dialogue."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government, defying world criticism, had pushed
forward with its plan to construct a Jewish neighborhood in
traditionally Arab east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Ross was dispatched by Clinton to the Middle East
for talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in an attempt to stop the peace
process from derailing.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Ross returned to Washington late Friday "not empty
handed," but he admitted, "There's a lot of hard work to do."
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman John Dinger told reporters that
Ross, whose mission to the Middle East was to assess the situation
and find what would be the best way to move forward the peace
process, had spoken "extensively" with Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
But Dinger declined to make any comment on Ross's trip, which
was seen by analysts here as a failure to reverse the tense
situation.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday night, Arab foreign ministers agreed at a Cairo
meeting to recommend that their countries suspend normal relations
with Israel, restore an economic boycott, close down Israeli
diplomatic missions and withdraw from multilateral peace talks
until Israel shows greater flexibility.
</P>
<P>
Dinger indicated that Albright might travel to the Middle East
"when it is helpful and useful."
</P>
<P>
Both McCurry and Dinger announced the arrival of King Hussein
of Jordan and a meeting with Clinton Tuesday, which was postponed
from March 18 after a deranged Jordanian soldier killed seven
Israeli schoolgirls near the Jordan-Israel border.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein is the fourth of a series of Middle East leaders
coming to Washington for talks with Clinton after a deal on Hebron
was signed between the Israelis and Palestinians in January.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was the first who had talks with Clinton, which were
followed by Arafat and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
