<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Army Gen. Clark Nominated as Top NATO Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has picked Army General Wesley Clark to become the next top
commander of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), the
White House announced today.
</P>
<P>
Clark, 52, who is expected to succeed General George Joulwan,
will also be head of the U.S. forces in Europe, White House
spokesman Michael McCurry told a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Joulwan is expected to retire this summer.
</P>
<P>
"This nomination is subject to the approval of the North
Atlantic Council," he said. "We are actively consulting now, of
course, with our North Atlantic Treaty allies."
</P>
<P>
The nomination of Clark as commander-in-chief of the U.S.
European Command will need the approval of the U.S. Congress, the
spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Clark brings to the job both a knowledge of Russia and
extensive experience with the Bosnia problem. He was the senior
military member in the team brokering the 1995 Dayton peace
accords that ended the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
A West Point graduate, Clark is now head of the U.S. Southern
Command, overseeing U.S. military operations in Central and South
America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
