<DOCNO> XIE19970401.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Personal Incomes Up by 0.9 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 31 (Xinhua) -- The personal incomes in the
U.S. surged by 0.9 percent in February, the largest gain in eight
months, the U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the personal incomes were earned at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6.71 trillion dollars in the
month. It was the largest advance in incomes since June 1996 and
more than doubled January's revised 0.4 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
Private wages and salaries, the most closely watched component
of income, surged by 1.5 percent in February after declining 0.2
percent in the month before.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the personal spending in February was at an
annual rate of 5.33 trillion dollars, up by 0.3 percent, the
smallest since September 1996.
</P>
<P>
But the increase followed a revised 1 percent gain in January,
the best in 11 months. The previous estimate increase of spending
in January was 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report showed consumers in the first two months of the year
spent at about the same robust rate as in the final three months of
last year, when consumers helped boost economic growth to a strong
3.8 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
Spending on durable goods rose by 0.1 percent. It gained by 0.3
percent on nondurable goods and by 0.4 percent on services.
</P>
<P>
Disposable personal income, income after taxes, grew by 0.8
percent in February after a 0.7 percent gain in the month before.
</P>
<P>
The combination of strong income growth and a modest spending
increase boosted Americans' savings rate -- savings as a
percentage of disposable income -- to 5.5 percent in February, the
best in five months.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. analysts said that spending and income growth in
February may lead the U.S. Federal Reserve to further raise the
interest rate to wring inflationary pressures from the economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
